1
00:01:42,519 --> 00:01:46,273
[WOMAN VOCALIZING]

2
00:01:57,826 --> 00:01:59,954
[CHILDREN LAUGHING]

3
00:02:08,587 --> 00:02:11,423
[WIND BLOWING]

4
00:02:36,073 --> 00:02:38,659
[♪♪♪]

5
00:02:38,659 --> 00:02:40,619
[HORSE WHINNIES]

6
00:02:43,288 --> 00:02:45,332
[WHINNYING]

7
00:02:58,679 --> 00:03:01,098
[MEN SHOUTING]

8
00:03:08,605 --> 00:03:11,190
[HORSES WHINNYING]

9
00:03:16,738 --> 00:03:18,239
Sir.

10
00:03:18,239 --> 00:03:19,825
General.

11
00:03:19,825 --> 00:03:21,493
General.

12
00:03:21,493 --> 00:03:23,537
Sir.
General.

13
00:03:24,955 --> 00:03:27,457
Sir.
General.

14
00:03:27,457 --> 00:03:28,667
General.

15
00:03:28,667 --> 00:03:31,419
[MAN SHOUTS]
Sir.

16
00:03:31,419 --> 00:03:33,505
[MEN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

17
00:03:46,434 --> 00:03:48,187
Lean and hungry.

18
00:03:51,190 --> 00:03:54,234
Still nothing?
Not a sign.

19
00:03:54,234 --> 00:03:57,278
How long has he been gone?
Nearly two hours.

20
00:04:00,032 --> 00:04:03,242
Will they fight, sir?
We shall know soon enough.

21
00:04:03,242 --> 00:04:05,954
Soldier, I ordered you
to move those catapults forward.

22
00:04:05,954 --> 00:04:07,748
They're out of range.
Range is good.

23
00:04:09,541 --> 00:04:11,376
The danger to the cavalry--

24
00:04:11,376 --> 00:04:13,503
It is acceptable.
Agreed?

25
00:04:13,503 --> 00:04:16,215
[MAN SHOUTING IN GERMAN]

26
00:04:16,215 --> 00:04:18,884
[SHOUTING CONTINUES]

27
00:04:22,179 --> 00:04:24,223
They say no.

28
00:04:24,223 --> 00:04:27,101
[WHINNYING]

29
00:04:33,273 --> 00:04:35,817
[WHINNYING]
Steady! Steady!

30
00:04:37,778 --> 00:04:41,115
[SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

31
00:04:41,115 --> 00:04:44,409
[MEN SHOUTING IN GERMAN]

32
00:04:44,409 --> 00:04:47,871
[SHOUTING]

33
00:04:49,998 --> 00:04:52,251
People should know
when they're conquered.

34
00:04:58,257 --> 00:05:00,550
[SHOUTING]

35
00:05:00,550 --> 00:05:03,178
[THUNDEROUS SHOUTING]

36
00:05:03,178 --> 00:05:07,057
Would you, Quintus?
Would I?

37
00:05:12,646 --> 00:05:14,231
[WHINING]

38
00:05:19,236 --> 00:05:22,114
[SHOUTING CONTINUES]

39
00:05:23,157 --> 00:05:24,491
Strength and honor.

40
00:05:24,491 --> 00:05:26,534
Strength and honor.
Strength and honor.

41
00:05:32,166 --> 00:05:35,334
At my signal,
unleash hell.

42
00:05:37,963 --> 00:05:39,881
[WHINING]

43
00:05:52,435 --> 00:05:55,272
[SHOUTING]

44
00:05:58,066 --> 00:06:00,359
Load the catapults.

45
00:06:00,359 --> 00:06:02,321
Infantry form up
for advance.

46
00:06:03,864 --> 00:06:06,365
Archers ready.
Archers!

47
00:06:06,365 --> 00:06:08,118
Nock!
Nock!

48
00:06:12,664 --> 00:06:14,791
[SHOUTING]

49
00:06:31,599 --> 00:06:35,103
Patres!
MEN: Maximus!

50
00:06:36,688 --> 00:06:40,567
Three weeks from now,
I will be harvesting my crops.

51
00:06:40,567 --> 00:06:42,777
Imagine where you will be,

52
00:06:42,777 --> 00:06:45,864
and it will be so.

53
00:06:45,864 --> 00:06:49,408
Hold the line!
Stay with me!

54
00:06:49,408 --> 00:06:52,079
If you find yourself alone,

55
00:06:52,079 --> 00:06:54,748
riding in green fields
with the sun on your face,

56
00:06:56,291 --> 00:06:58,960
do not be troubled.

57
00:06:58,960 --> 00:07:00,795
For you are in Elysium,

58
00:07:00,795 --> 00:07:03,090
and you're already dead!

59
00:07:03,090 --> 00:07:05,175
[LAUGHING]

60
00:07:05,175 --> 00:07:06,927
Brothers,

61
00:07:08,053 --> 00:07:11,014
what we do in life...

62
00:07:11,014 --> 00:07:13,183
echoes in eternity.

63
00:07:13,183 --> 00:07:15,518
[SHOUTING]

64
00:07:19,940 --> 00:07:21,066
[GRUNTING]

65
00:07:21,066 --> 00:07:22,442
Pull!

66
00:07:29,950 --> 00:07:31,076
Pull!

67
00:07:31,076 --> 00:07:32,994
Pull!

68
00:07:37,916 --> 00:07:39,960
MAN:
Catapults ready, sir!

69
00:07:50,929 --> 00:07:53,348
Archers, ignite!

70
00:07:53,348 --> 00:07:54,473
Ignite!

71
00:07:54,473 --> 00:07:56,059
Ignite!

72
00:08:01,606 --> 00:08:04,318
MAN:
Archers, draw!

73
00:08:07,946 --> 00:08:09,072
Loose!

74
00:08:10,740 --> 00:08:11,908
Loose!

75
00:08:16,788 --> 00:08:18,123
[SHATTERING]

76
00:08:20,708 --> 00:08:21,835
Aah!

77
00:08:22,836 --> 00:08:24,587
Aaarggh!

78
00:08:28,675 --> 00:08:30,218
Aah!
Aah!

79
00:08:34,889 --> 00:08:36,224
[SHOUTING]

80
00:08:38,226 --> 00:08:41,562
MAN:
All right, men, ready!

81
00:08:45,650 --> 00:08:48,320
MAXIMUS:
Hold the line!

82
00:08:48,320 --> 00:08:49,946
[SHOUTING]

83
00:08:53,908 --> 00:08:56,411
Draw!
Loose!

84
00:08:56,411 --> 00:08:58,705
Loose!
Loose!

85
00:08:58,705 --> 00:09:00,707
Reload!

86
00:09:04,919 --> 00:09:07,422
MAXIMUS:
Hold the line!

87
00:09:07,422 --> 00:09:08,548
Draw!

88
00:09:08,548 --> 00:09:09,674
Loose!

89
00:09:12,344 --> 00:09:14,221
MAXIMUS:
Stay with me!

90
00:09:18,975 --> 00:09:20,852
Stay with me!

91
00:09:25,899 --> 00:09:27,150
[SHOUTING]

92
00:09:33,740 --> 00:09:36,076
[SHOUTING]

93
00:09:41,915 --> 00:09:43,250
Aaarggh!

94
00:09:49,381 --> 00:09:52,426
MAXIMUS:
Roma Victor!

95
00:09:52,426 --> 00:09:54,802
[IN UNISON]
Roma Victor!

96
00:09:54,802 --> 00:09:56,221
[SHOUTING]

97
00:10:09,109 --> 00:10:10,444
Aah!

98
00:10:12,571 --> 00:10:13,863
[GRUNTING]

99
00:10:20,412 --> 00:10:21,955
Aah!

100
00:10:29,546 --> 00:10:30,629
[GRUNTING]

101
00:10:36,511 --> 00:10:37,887
Aah!

102
00:10:41,057 --> 00:10:42,642
[GROANING]

103
00:10:44,227 --> 00:10:45,479
Aah!

104
00:10:48,231 --> 00:10:49,274
Aah!

105
00:10:49,274 --> 00:10:50,900
Aaarggh!

106
00:10:54,112 --> 00:10:55,822
[GRUNTING]

107
00:10:59,951 --> 00:11:01,119
Aah!

108
00:11:07,542 --> 00:11:09,628
Aah!

109
00:11:14,799 --> 00:11:16,968
Aah!

110
00:11:17,844 --> 00:11:21,139
[GRUNTING]
[BARKING]

111
00:11:26,478 --> 00:11:29,189
[GROWLING]

112
00:11:30,315 --> 00:11:33,109
[DOG SNARLING, BARKING]

113
00:11:33,109 --> 00:11:35,320
[♪♪♪]

114
00:11:44,538 --> 00:11:46,122
Aah!

115
00:11:56,341 --> 00:11:59,093
[NEIGHS]

116
00:12:05,642 --> 00:12:06,976
[SHRIEKS]

117
00:12:13,107 --> 00:12:15,610
[PANTING]

118
00:12:18,363 --> 00:12:20,823
[PANTING]

119
00:12:25,370 --> 00:12:27,622
Roma Victor!

120
00:12:27,622 --> 00:12:31,125
[CHEERING]

121
00:12:51,271 --> 00:12:52,855
[HORSES NEIGHING]

122
00:13:08,913 --> 00:13:11,207
Do you think
he's really dying?

123
00:13:13,126 --> 00:13:15,295
He's been dying
for 10 years.

124
00:13:15,295 --> 00:13:18,632
If he weren't really dying,
he wouldn't have sent for us.

125
00:13:19,549 --> 00:13:21,884
Maybe he just
misses us.

126
00:13:21,884 --> 00:13:23,386
And the senators?

127
00:13:23,386 --> 00:13:25,972
He wouldn't have summoned them--
Peace, Commodus.

128
00:13:25,972 --> 00:13:27,599
After two weeks on
the road,

129
00:13:27,599 --> 00:13:29,892
your incessant scheming
is hurting my head.

130
00:13:36,608 --> 00:13:38,777
He's made
his decision.

131
00:13:38,777 --> 00:13:41,070
He's going to announce it.

132
00:13:44,157 --> 00:13:46,117
He will name me.

133
00:13:48,911 --> 00:13:51,706
The first thing I shall do...

134
00:13:51,706 --> 00:13:53,750
when--

135
00:13:55,543 --> 00:13:58,630
Is honor him with games
worthy of His Majesty.

136
00:13:58,630 --> 00:14:03,884
For now, the first thing
I shall do is have a hot bath.

137
00:14:03,884 --> 00:14:05,428
[KNOCKING]

138
00:14:05,428 --> 00:14:07,180
MAN:
Your Highness?

139
00:14:10,266 --> 00:14:12,519
MAN:
We seem to be
almost there, sir.

140
00:14:19,275 --> 00:14:21,319
Sire.
Where's the Emperor?

141
00:14:21,319 --> 00:14:24,531
He's at the front, sire.
They've been gone for 19 days.

142
00:14:24,531 --> 00:14:27,241
The wounded are
still coming in.

143
00:14:27,241 --> 00:14:29,202
My horse.

144
00:14:29,202 --> 00:14:31,287
MAN:
My lord.

145
00:14:33,832 --> 00:14:36,501
Kiss?

146
00:14:36,501 --> 00:14:38,252
[NEIGHING]

147
00:14:55,770 --> 00:14:58,773
[MAN SHOUTING ORDERS
IN DISTANCE]

148
00:15:10,535 --> 00:15:12,787
You have proved
your valor...

149
00:15:12,787 --> 00:15:15,832
yet again, Maximus.

150
00:15:16,999 --> 00:15:19,960
Let us hope
for the last time.

151
00:15:19,960 --> 00:15:21,838
There's no one left
to fight, sire.

152
00:15:21,838 --> 00:15:25,174
Ah. There is always
someone left to fight.

153
00:15:25,174 --> 00:15:28,261
How can I reward
Rome's greatest general?

154
00:15:33,015 --> 00:15:34,851
Let me go home.

155
00:15:36,269 --> 00:15:39,063
Ah. Home.

156
00:15:39,063 --> 00:15:41,274
[♪♪♪]

157
00:15:45,403 --> 00:15:47,405
Whoa! Whoa!

158
00:15:47,405 --> 00:15:50,950
[CHEERING]

159
00:15:57,081 --> 00:15:59,375
They honor you,
Caesar.

160
00:15:59,375 --> 00:16:02,253
It's for you, Maximus.
They honor you.

161
00:16:02,253 --> 00:16:05,298
[CHEERING]

162
00:16:10,136 --> 00:16:12,388
[CHEERING INTENSIFIES]

163
00:16:22,607 --> 00:16:24,901
MAN:
Roma Victor!

164
00:16:24,901 --> 00:16:27,904
Have I missed it?
Have I missed the battle?

165
00:16:28,905 --> 00:16:30,824
You have missed
the war.

166
00:16:30,824 --> 00:16:33,743
Father, congratulations.

167
00:16:33,743 --> 00:16:36,245
I shall sacrifice a hundred
bulls to honor your triumph.

168
00:16:36,245 --> 00:16:38,164
Save the bulls.

169
00:16:38,164 --> 00:16:40,541
Honor Maximus.
He won the battle.

170
00:16:40,541 --> 00:16:44,838
General.
Highness.

171
00:16:44,838 --> 00:16:47,882
Rome salutes you,
and I embrace you as a brother.

172
00:16:47,882 --> 00:16:50,176
It has been too long,
my old friend.

173
00:16:50,176 --> 00:16:52,386
Highness.
Here, Father.

174
00:16:52,386 --> 00:16:55,807
Take my arm.

175
00:16:55,807 --> 00:16:58,852
I think it is time
for me to leave.

176
00:17:13,574 --> 00:17:17,203
So much for
the glory of Rome.

177
00:17:28,756 --> 00:17:32,176
[CHATTER, LAUGHTER, MUSIC]

178
00:17:37,724 --> 00:17:39,726
Magnificent battle.

179
00:18:03,249 --> 00:18:05,209
General.
Still alive?

180
00:18:05,209 --> 00:18:06,544
Still alive?

181
00:18:06,544 --> 00:18:08,379
The gods must have
a sense of humor.

182
00:18:08,379 --> 00:18:11,131
The gods must love you.
Valerius.

183
00:18:11,131 --> 00:18:13,760
Back to barracks,
General? Or to Rome?

184
00:18:13,760 --> 00:18:16,930
Home. My wife,
the son, the harvest.

185
00:18:16,930 --> 00:18:21,099
Maximus the farmer. I still have
difficulty imagining that.

186
00:18:21,099 --> 00:18:24,771
You know, dirt cleans off a lot
easier than blood, Quintus.

187
00:18:24,771 --> 00:18:27,189
There he is.
Highness.

188
00:18:27,189 --> 00:18:29,149
Senator Gaius,
Senator Falco.

189
00:18:29,149 --> 00:18:30,735
Beware of Gaius.

190
00:18:30,735 --> 00:18:32,528
He'll pour a honeyed
potion in your ear,

191
00:18:32,528 --> 00:18:34,614
and you'll wake up one day,
and all you'll say is,

192
00:18:34,614 --> 00:18:36,198
"Republic, republic, republic."

193
00:18:36,198 --> 00:18:38,492
Well, why not?
Rome was founded as a republic.

194
00:18:38,492 --> 00:18:41,454
Yes, and in a republic
the Senate has the power.

195
00:18:41,454 --> 00:18:43,998
But Senator Gaius isn't
influenced by that, of course.

196
00:18:43,998 --> 00:18:46,667
Where do you stand, General?
Emperor or Senate?

197
00:18:46,667 --> 00:18:48,544
The soldier has the advantage
of being able

198
00:18:48,544 --> 00:18:52,048
to look his enemy
in the eye, Senator.

199
00:18:52,048 --> 00:18:53,967
GAIUS:
Well, with an army
behind you,

200
00:18:53,967 --> 00:18:55,885
you could be
extremely political.

201
00:18:55,885 --> 00:18:59,013
I warned you.
Now I shall save you. Senators.

202
00:19:08,815 --> 00:19:11,191
Maximus.

203
00:19:11,191 --> 00:19:14,070
I'm going to need
good men like you.

204
00:19:15,780 --> 00:19:18,699
How may I be of service,
Highness?

205
00:19:18,699 --> 00:19:21,828
You're a man who knows
what it is to command.

206
00:19:21,828 --> 00:19:23,162
You give your orders,

207
00:19:23,162 --> 00:19:25,205
the orders are obeyed,
and the battle is won.

208
00:19:25,205 --> 00:19:26,582
But these senators,

209
00:19:26,582 --> 00:19:30,003
they scheme and squabble
and flatter and deceive.

210
00:19:30,003 --> 00:19:33,589
Maximus, we must save Rome
from the politicians, my friend.

211
00:19:33,589 --> 00:19:37,093
Can I count on you...
when the time comes?

212
00:19:42,807 --> 00:19:44,684
Highness, when
your father releases me,

213
00:19:44,684 --> 00:19:46,226
I intend to return home.

214
00:19:46,226 --> 00:19:50,439
Home? Well,
no one's earned it more.

215
00:19:50,439 --> 00:19:54,443
Don't get too comfortable.
I may call on you before long.

216
00:19:56,112 --> 00:19:59,490
Lucilla's here.
Did you know?

217
00:19:59,490 --> 00:20:02,160
She's not forgotten you.

218
00:20:02,160 --> 00:20:04,745
And now
you're the great man.

219
00:20:08,332 --> 00:20:10,668
[MUSIC, CHATTERING CONTINUES]

220
00:20:16,757 --> 00:20:19,343
If only you
had been born a man.

221
00:20:20,594 --> 00:20:22,889
What a caesar
you would have made.

222
00:20:24,598 --> 00:20:26,600
Father.

223
00:20:31,898 --> 00:20:33,983
You would have
been strong.

224
00:20:33,983 --> 00:20:37,361
I wonder,
would you have been just?

225
00:20:37,361 --> 00:20:40,073
I would have been
what you taught me to be.

226
00:20:40,073 --> 00:20:42,408
Oh.

227
00:20:42,408 --> 00:20:44,535
How was your journey?

228
00:20:44,535 --> 00:20:48,706
Long. Uncomfortable.
Why have I come?

229
00:20:48,706 --> 00:20:51,375
I need your help.
With your brother.

230
00:20:51,375 --> 00:20:53,502
[CHUCKLING]
Of course.

231
00:20:53,502 --> 00:20:55,713
He loves you.
He always has.

232
00:20:56,672 --> 00:20:58,382
And...

233
00:20:59,717 --> 00:21:03,221
he will need you now
more than ever.

234
00:21:07,516 --> 00:21:09,894
Enough of politics.

235
00:21:09,894 --> 00:21:13,606
Let us pretend that you
are a loving daughter...

236
00:21:13,606 --> 00:21:16,358
and I am a good father.

237
00:21:21,572 --> 00:21:25,201
This is a pleasant fiction,
isn't it?

238
00:21:27,245 --> 00:21:29,122
[DOG BARKING]

239
00:21:30,748 --> 00:21:35,878
[MAN SHOUTING]

240
00:21:35,878 --> 00:21:37,255
[DOG BARKING IN DISTANCE]

241
00:21:37,255 --> 00:21:39,298
MAN:
Good morning.

242
00:21:48,724 --> 00:21:51,560
[BLEATING]

243
00:21:51,560 --> 00:21:54,647
MAN:
I need three more horses.

244
00:21:57,316 --> 00:22:00,360
[WHINNYING]

245
00:22:04,323 --> 00:22:06,533
COMMODUS:
Two! Three!

246
00:22:06,533 --> 00:22:08,619
Four!
[BLADES CLANKING]

247
00:22:08,619 --> 00:22:11,622
One! Two!

248
00:22:15,835 --> 00:22:17,711
[GRUNTING]

249
00:22:27,013 --> 00:22:29,015
You sent for me,
Caesar?

250
00:22:32,935 --> 00:22:34,478
Caesar?

251
00:22:34,478 --> 00:22:37,815
Tell me again, Maximus.

252
00:22:37,815 --> 00:22:40,734
Why are we here?

253
00:22:40,734 --> 00:22:43,737
For the glory of
the Empire, sire.

254
00:22:43,737 --> 00:22:45,781
Ah, yes.

255
00:22:46,740 --> 00:22:49,285
Ah, yes,
I remember.

256
00:22:51,578 --> 00:22:54,290
Do you see that map,
Maximus?

257
00:22:54,290 --> 00:22:57,168
That is the world
which I created.

258
00:22:58,627 --> 00:23:00,963
For 25 years...

259
00:23:00,963 --> 00:23:05,801
I have conquered, spilt blood,
expanded the Empire.

260
00:23:05,801 --> 00:23:09,722
Since I became caesar, I've
known four years without war.

261
00:23:09,722 --> 00:23:12,308
Four years of peace
in 20.

262
00:23:12,308 --> 00:23:15,019
And for what?

263
00:23:15,019 --> 00:23:17,437
[HORSE NEIGHING IN DISTANCE]

264
00:23:21,399 --> 00:23:25,154
I brought the sword.
Nothing more.

265
00:23:25,154 --> 00:23:27,948
Caesar, your life--

266
00:23:27,948 --> 00:23:30,117
Please.
Please don't call me that.

267
00:23:31,077 --> 00:23:33,746
Come.
Please.

268
00:23:33,746 --> 00:23:36,165
Come sit.

269
00:23:36,165 --> 00:23:39,001
Let us talk
together now...

270
00:23:39,001 --> 00:23:41,921
very simply,
as men.

271
00:23:41,921 --> 00:23:45,799
Well, Maximus...

272
00:23:45,799 --> 00:23:47,301
talk.

273
00:23:50,846 --> 00:23:53,266
Five thousand of my men are
out there in the freezing mud.

274
00:23:53,266 --> 00:23:55,433
Three thousand of them
are bloodied and cleaved.

275
00:23:55,433 --> 00:23:57,477
Two thousand will never
leave this place.

276
00:23:57,477 --> 00:24:00,647
I will not believe that they
fought and died for nothing.

277
00:24:00,647 --> 00:24:02,233
And what would you
believe, Maximus--?

278
00:24:02,233 --> 00:24:06,195
They fought for you...
And for Rome.

279
00:24:06,195 --> 00:24:08,239
And what is Rome,
Maximus?

280
00:24:10,074 --> 00:24:12,659
I've seen much of
the rest of the world.

281
00:24:12,659 --> 00:24:16,747
It is brutal and cruel and dark.
Rome is the light.

282
00:24:16,747 --> 00:24:18,749
Yet you have
never been there.

283
00:24:18,749 --> 00:24:21,252
You have not seen
what it has become.

284
00:24:21,252 --> 00:24:24,546
I am dying, Maximus.

285
00:24:24,546 --> 00:24:26,464
When a man sees his end,

286
00:24:26,464 --> 00:24:30,094
he wants to know there was
some purpose to his life.

287
00:24:30,094 --> 00:24:33,680
How will the world speak my name
in years to come?

288
00:24:33,680 --> 00:24:35,975
Will I be known
as the philosopher?

289
00:24:35,975 --> 00:24:40,854
The warrior?
The tyrant?

290
00:24:40,854 --> 00:24:46,526
Or will I be the emperor who
gave Rome back her true self?

291
00:24:46,526 --> 00:24:48,737
There was once a dream
that was Rome.

292
00:24:48,737 --> 00:24:51,824
You could only
whisper it.

293
00:24:51,824 --> 00:24:54,868
Anything more than a whisper
and it would vanish.

294
00:24:54,868 --> 00:24:57,163
It was so fragile.

295
00:24:57,163 --> 00:25:00,916
And I fear that it will not
survive the winter.

296
00:25:02,542 --> 00:25:04,753
Maximus,

297
00:25:04,753 --> 00:25:07,756
let us whisper now,

298
00:25:07,756 --> 00:25:09,549
together,
you and I.

299
00:25:09,549 --> 00:25:11,260
You have a son.

300
00:25:13,012 --> 00:25:14,847
Tell me about your home.

301
00:25:21,687 --> 00:25:24,773
My house is in the hills
above Trujillo.

302
00:25:24,773 --> 00:25:26,692
A very simple place.

303
00:25:27,943 --> 00:25:31,030
Pink stones
that warm in the sun.

304
00:25:31,030 --> 00:25:35,075
A kitchen garden that
smells of herbs in the day,

305
00:25:35,075 --> 00:25:36,994
jasmine in the evening.

306
00:25:38,578 --> 00:25:41,623
Through the gate
is a giant poplar.

307
00:25:41,623 --> 00:25:44,460
Figs, apples, pears.

308
00:25:44,460 --> 00:25:46,586
The soil, Marcus--
Black.

309
00:25:46,586 --> 00:25:49,507
Black like my wife's hair.
[CHUCKLES]

310
00:25:49,507 --> 00:25:51,842
Grapes on the south slopes,
olives on the north.

311
00:25:51,842 --> 00:25:53,260
Wild ponies play near my house.

312
00:25:53,260 --> 00:25:55,762
They tease my son.
He wants to be one of them.

313
00:25:55,762 --> 00:25:57,473
When was the last time
you were home?

314
00:25:57,473 --> 00:26:00,809
Two years, 264 days,
and this morning.

315
00:26:02,395 --> 00:26:04,688
I envy you, Maximus.

316
00:26:04,688 --> 00:26:08,484
It's a good home.
Worth fighting for?

317
00:26:10,694 --> 00:26:12,154
[SIGHS]

318
00:26:12,154 --> 00:26:14,407
There is
one more duty...

319
00:26:14,407 --> 00:26:17,201
that I ask of you
before you go home.

320
00:26:19,161 --> 00:26:21,497
What would you
have me do, Caesar?

321
00:26:21,497 --> 00:26:22,873
I want you to become

322
00:26:22,873 --> 00:26:26,252
the protector
of Rome after I die.

323
00:26:26,252 --> 00:26:29,463
I will empower you
to one end alone.

324
00:26:29,463 --> 00:26:33,759
To give power back
to the people of Rome...

325
00:26:33,759 --> 00:26:36,887
and end the corruption
that has crippled it.

326
00:26:43,102 --> 00:26:46,480
Will you accept this great honor
that I have offered you?

327
00:26:48,148 --> 00:26:50,234
With all my heart, no.

328
00:26:52,361 --> 00:26:54,780
Maximus,

329
00:26:54,780 --> 00:26:57,575
that is why
it must be you.

330
00:26:57,575 --> 00:26:59,368
But surely a prefect,
a senator,

331
00:26:59,368 --> 00:27:01,120
somebody who knows
the city,

332
00:27:01,120 --> 00:27:02,955
who understands
her politics.

333
00:27:02,955 --> 00:27:05,832
But you have not been
corrupted by her politics.

334
00:27:10,796 --> 00:27:15,050
And Commodus?
Commodus is not a moral man.

335
00:27:15,050 --> 00:27:17,470
You have known that
since you were young.

336
00:27:17,470 --> 00:27:20,055
Commodus cannot rule.

337
00:27:20,055 --> 00:27:22,391
He must not rule.

338
00:27:23,850 --> 00:27:26,686
You are the son
that I should have had.

339
00:27:29,189 --> 00:27:32,610
Commodus will accept
my decision.

340
00:27:34,612 --> 00:27:39,241
He knows that you command
the loyalty of the army.

341
00:27:42,744 --> 00:27:46,123
I.. I need
some time, sire.

342
00:27:46,123 --> 00:27:47,374
Yes.

343
00:27:47,374 --> 00:27:52,087
By sunset,
I hope you will have agreed.

344
00:27:52,087 --> 00:27:55,007
Now embrace me as my son.

345
00:27:57,717 --> 00:28:00,471
And bring an old man
another blanket.

346
00:28:16,195 --> 00:28:17,779
LUCILLA:
My father favors you now.

347
00:28:17,779 --> 00:28:18,822
My lady.

348
00:28:18,822 --> 00:28:21,200
It was not always so.

349
00:28:21,200 --> 00:28:23,410
Many things change.

350
00:28:23,410 --> 00:28:26,246
Many things.
Not everything.

351
00:28:28,874 --> 00:28:30,959
Maximus, stop.

352
00:28:34,254 --> 00:28:36,298
Let me see your face.

353
00:28:37,383 --> 00:28:39,759
Hm.
You seem upset.

354
00:28:39,759 --> 00:28:42,346
I lost many men.

355
00:28:42,346 --> 00:28:45,015
What did my father
want with you?

356
00:28:45,015 --> 00:28:47,976
[SIGHING]
To wish me well
before I leave for home.

357
00:28:49,019 --> 00:28:51,146
You're lying.

358
00:28:51,146 --> 00:28:52,814
I could always tell
when you were lying

359
00:28:52,814 --> 00:28:54,525
because you were never
any good at it.

360
00:28:54,525 --> 00:28:57,361
I never acquired
your comfort with it.
True.

361
00:28:57,361 --> 00:28:59,779
But then you never had to.

362
00:28:59,779 --> 00:29:02,575
Life is more simple
for a soldier.

363
00:29:04,368 --> 00:29:07,329
Or do you
think me heartless?

364
00:29:07,329 --> 00:29:10,708
I think you have
a talent for survival.

365
00:29:13,627 --> 00:29:16,338
[LAUGHS]

366
00:29:16,338 --> 00:29:17,964
Maximus, stop.

367
00:29:17,964 --> 00:29:19,633
[LAUGHING CONTINUES]

368
00:29:19,633 --> 00:29:22,553
Is it really so terrible
seeing me again?

369
00:29:22,553 --> 00:29:26,056
No. I'm tired
from battle.

370
00:29:26,056 --> 00:29:29,059
It hurts you to see
my father so fragile.

371
00:29:32,354 --> 00:29:34,147
Commodus expects that
my father will

372
00:29:34,147 --> 00:29:36,108
announce his succession
within days.

373
00:29:37,859 --> 00:29:40,738
Will you serve my brother
as you served his father?

374
00:29:43,198 --> 00:29:45,534
I will always
serve Rome.

375
00:29:47,453 --> 00:29:49,246
Do you know,

376
00:29:49,246 --> 00:29:51,789
I still remember you
in my prayers.

377
00:29:52,832 --> 00:29:57,003
Oh, yes. I pray.

378
00:30:00,466 --> 00:30:02,718
I was sad to hear
of your husband's death.

379
00:30:02,718 --> 00:30:04,052
I mourned him.

380
00:30:05,512 --> 00:30:08,390
Thank you.
And I hear you have a son.

381
00:30:09,975 --> 00:30:13,479
Yes. Lucius.

382
00:30:13,479 --> 00:30:15,897
He'll be nearly
8 years old.

383
00:30:15,897 --> 00:30:18,442
My son is also
nearly 8.

384
00:30:20,944 --> 00:30:23,238
I thank you
for your prayers.

385
00:30:31,079 --> 00:30:34,958
MAXIMUS:
Ancestors, I ask
for your guidance.

386
00:30:34,958 --> 00:30:36,502
Blessed mother,

387
00:30:36,502 --> 00:30:40,005
come to me with the gods'
desire for my future.

388
00:30:40,005 --> 00:30:43,467
Blessed father, watch over my
wife and son with a ready sword.

389
00:30:45,218 --> 00:30:48,888
Whisper to them, I live
only to hold them again.

390
00:30:48,888 --> 00:30:52,601
Ancestors,
I honor you...

391
00:30:52,601 --> 00:30:55,729
and will try to live with
the dignity you have taught me.

392
00:31:18,210 --> 00:31:19,837
Cicero?

393
00:31:23,256 --> 00:31:25,050
Sir.

394
00:31:30,096 --> 00:31:32,182
You don't find it hard
to do your duty?

395
00:31:35,268 --> 00:31:38,689
Sometimes I do
what I want to do.

396
00:31:38,689 --> 00:31:41,483
The rest of the time
I do what I have to.

397
00:31:44,236 --> 00:31:47,197
We may not be able
to go home after all.

398
00:31:53,579 --> 00:31:55,706
[WIND BLOWING]

399
00:32:16,643 --> 00:32:19,563
MARCUS:
Are you ready to do
your duty for Rome?

400
00:32:22,399 --> 00:32:23,942
Yes, Father.

401
00:32:25,193 --> 00:32:27,446
You will not
be emperor.

402
00:32:30,031 --> 00:32:33,118
Which wiser, older man
is to take my place?

403
00:32:33,118 --> 00:32:36,538
My powers
will pass to Maximus...

404
00:32:36,538 --> 00:32:38,749
to hold in trust...

405
00:32:38,749 --> 00:32:43,420
until the Senate
is ready to rule once more.

406
00:32:43,420 --> 00:32:48,216
Rome is to be
a republic again.

407
00:32:49,384 --> 00:32:52,679
Maximus.
Yes.

408
00:32:57,601 --> 00:33:00,186
My decision
disappoints you?

409
00:33:03,899 --> 00:33:05,901
You wrote to me once,

410
00:33:07,861 --> 00:33:11,490
listing
the four chief virtues.

411
00:33:11,490 --> 00:33:12,950
Wisdom,

412
00:33:12,950 --> 00:33:16,870
justice, fortitude...

413
00:33:16,870 --> 00:33:18,371
and temperance.

414
00:33:20,833 --> 00:33:24,837
As I read the list,
I knew I had none of them.

415
00:33:24,837 --> 00:33:27,005
But I have
other virtues, Father.

416
00:33:28,465 --> 00:33:31,009
Ambition.

417
00:33:31,009 --> 00:33:34,262
That can be a virtue
when it drives us to excel.

418
00:33:35,514 --> 00:33:39,017
Resourcefulness.
Courage.

419
00:33:39,017 --> 00:33:42,187
Perhaps not on
the battlefield, but...

420
00:33:42,187 --> 00:33:45,607
there are
many forms of courage.

421
00:33:45,607 --> 00:33:49,110
Devotion...
to my family...

422
00:33:49,110 --> 00:33:51,738
and to you.

423
00:33:52,990 --> 00:33:55,701
But none of my virtues
were on your list.

424
00:33:57,744 --> 00:34:00,873
Even then it was as if
you didn't want me for your son.

425
00:34:00,873 --> 00:34:03,416
Oh, Commodus.

426
00:34:03,416 --> 00:34:06,003
You go too far.

427
00:34:06,003 --> 00:34:09,756
I search the faces
of the gods...

428
00:34:09,756 --> 00:34:14,761
for ways to please you,
to make you proud.

429
00:34:14,761 --> 00:34:17,180
One kind word,

430
00:34:17,180 --> 00:34:19,474
one full hug...

431
00:34:19,474 --> 00:34:24,229
where you pressed me
to your chest and held me tight,

432
00:34:24,229 --> 00:34:27,524
would have been like the sun on
my heart for a thousand years.

433
00:34:30,027 --> 00:34:32,487
What is it in me
you hate so much?

434
00:34:32,487 --> 00:34:33,906
Shh, Commodus.

435
00:34:35,532 --> 00:34:37,826
All I've ever wanted...

436
00:34:37,826 --> 00:34:42,622
was to live up to you,
Caesar.

437
00:34:42,622 --> 00:34:44,833
Father.

438
00:34:44,833 --> 00:34:46,292
Commodus...

439
00:34:50,505 --> 00:34:53,508
...your faults as a son

440
00:34:53,508 --> 00:34:57,512
is my failure as a father.

441
00:35:07,689 --> 00:35:09,357
Come.

442
00:35:12,611 --> 00:35:14,654
[SOBBING]
Father.

443
00:35:18,575 --> 00:35:21,244
[SOBBING CONTINUES]

444
00:35:29,544 --> 00:35:32,589
I would butcher
the whole world...

445
00:35:32,589 --> 00:35:35,425
if you would
only love me!

446
00:35:37,803 --> 00:35:39,554
[MARCUS GRUNTING]

447
00:35:46,853 --> 00:35:48,897
[MUFFLED GROANING]

448
00:35:54,069 --> 00:35:56,071
[GROANING]

449
00:36:12,587 --> 00:36:16,675
Maximus, the emperor needs you.
It's urgent.

450
00:36:21,429 --> 00:36:25,684
Lament with me, brother.
Our great father is dead.

451
00:36:52,961 --> 00:36:55,797
MAXIMUS:
How did he die?

452
00:36:55,797 --> 00:36:58,508
COMMODUS:
The surgeons say
there was no pain.

453
00:36:58,508 --> 00:37:00,760
His breath gave out
as he slept.

454
00:37:09,728 --> 00:37:11,855
Father.

455
00:37:14,149 --> 00:37:16,985
Your emperor asks
for your loyalty, Maximus.

456
00:37:18,319 --> 00:37:20,947
Take my hand.

457
00:37:22,866 --> 00:37:24,784
I only offer it once.

458
00:37:38,715 --> 00:37:40,717
Quintus.

459
00:38:08,120 --> 00:38:10,329
[SLAPPING]

460
00:38:30,225 --> 00:38:32,769
Hail, Caesar.

461
00:38:32,769 --> 00:38:35,480
I must talk to the senators.
I need their counsel.

462
00:38:35,480 --> 00:38:37,941
Wake Gaius and Falco.
Gaius and Falco.

463
00:38:37,941 --> 00:38:40,401
Sword.
Sword.

464
00:38:42,862 --> 00:38:46,158
Maximus, please be careful.
That was not prudent.

465
00:38:46,158 --> 00:38:48,910
Prudent?
The Emperor has been slain.

466
00:38:48,910 --> 00:38:52,164
QUINTUS:
The Emperor died
of natural causes.

467
00:38:52,164 --> 00:38:55,250
Why are you armed,
Quintus?
Guards!

468
00:38:58,295 --> 00:39:00,630
Please don't fight,
Maximus.

469
00:39:01,881 --> 00:39:05,051
QUINTUS:
I'm sorry.
Caesar has spoken.

470
00:39:05,051 --> 00:39:09,764
Ride until dawn...
and then execute him.

471
00:39:09,764 --> 00:39:12,267
Quintus, look at me.
Look at me!

472
00:39:12,267 --> 00:39:15,394
Promise me that you will
look after my family.

473
00:39:15,394 --> 00:39:18,982
Your family will meet you
in the afterlife.

474
00:39:18,982 --> 00:39:20,275
No!

475
00:39:20,275 --> 00:39:22,068
[THUNDERCLAP]

476
00:39:23,111 --> 00:39:25,113
[HORSES NEIGHING]

477
00:39:44,341 --> 00:39:46,968
Kneel.

478
00:39:48,678 --> 00:39:51,139
MAXIMUS:
Blessed Father,
watch over my wife and son.

479
00:39:51,139 --> 00:39:52,807
[SWORD UNSHEATHING]

480
00:39:52,807 --> 00:39:55,560
Whisper to them that I live
only to hold them again.

481
00:39:56,895 --> 00:39:59,356
At least give me
a clean death.

482
00:40:00,899 --> 00:40:02,942
A soldier's death.

483
00:40:16,622 --> 00:40:17,749
Aah!

484
00:40:18,875 --> 00:40:20,459
[GRUNTS]

485
00:40:20,459 --> 00:40:22,587
[GAGGING]

486
00:40:24,256 --> 00:40:25,965
The frost--

487
00:40:25,965 --> 00:40:28,509
Sometimes it makes
the blade stick.

488
00:40:28,509 --> 00:40:29,552
[GRUNTS]

489
00:40:29,552 --> 00:40:30,720
[HORSE NEIGHING]

490
00:40:39,520 --> 00:40:41,189
[SWORD WHIRRING]

491
00:40:41,189 --> 00:40:42,399
[GROANING]

492
00:40:48,113 --> 00:40:50,198
Praetorian!

493
00:40:51,408 --> 00:40:54,077
Hyah! Hyah!

494
00:41:00,833 --> 00:41:02,252
[GROANING]

495
00:41:15,681 --> 00:41:17,809
[GRUNTS]

496
00:41:22,855 --> 00:41:25,066
[♪♪♪]

497
00:41:44,461 --> 00:41:47,005
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

498
00:42:08,609 --> 00:42:11,528
MARCUS:
When was the last time
you were home?

499
00:42:11,528 --> 00:42:15,950
MAXIMUS:
Two years, 264 days,
and this morning.

500
00:42:15,950 --> 00:42:17,576
BOTH [OVERLAPPING]:
Blessed Father,

501
00:42:17,576 --> 00:42:20,663
watch over my wife and son
with a ready sword.

502
00:42:20,663 --> 00:42:23,416
Whisper to them I live only
to hold them again.

503
00:42:23,416 --> 00:42:25,293
For all else is dust and air.

504
00:42:25,293 --> 00:42:28,713
Whisper to them I
live only to hold them again.

505
00:42:28,713 --> 00:42:32,008
For all else is dust and air.

506
00:42:32,008 --> 00:42:35,011
[HORSE PANTING]

507
00:42:44,396 --> 00:42:46,605
[♪♪♪]

508
00:42:48,858 --> 00:42:51,694
[CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY,
LAUGHING]

509
00:42:57,574 --> 00:43:01,662
[BOY &amp; WOMAN SPEAKING
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

510
00:43:08,920 --> 00:43:10,629
[HORSES NEIGHING]

511
00:43:10,629 --> 00:43:12,382
[BOY SPEAKS IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

512
00:43:17,220 --> 00:43:19,638
[HOOFBEATS RUMBLING]

513
00:43:23,435 --> 00:43:25,644
[♪♪♪]

514
00:43:30,900 --> 00:43:33,069
[HORSES NEIGHING]
Papa! Papa!

515
00:43:38,575 --> 00:43:39,951
SOLDIER:
Hyah! Hyah!

516
00:43:44,747 --> 00:43:46,958
[♪♪♪]

517
00:43:59,762 --> 00:44:01,222
[NEIGHS]
[GRUNTS]

518
00:44:02,932 --> 00:44:06,894
[GROANING]
[NICKERING]

519
00:44:29,501 --> 00:44:32,962
[CHICKENS CLUCKING]

520
00:44:43,264 --> 00:44:46,476
[WOMAN VOCALIZING]

521
00:44:53,608 --> 00:44:56,693
[SOBBING]

522
00:45:13,169 --> 00:45:15,547
[MUTTERING, SOBBING]

523
00:45:28,685 --> 00:45:32,647
[WOMAN SINGING
