LANGUAGE]

526
00:46:02,218 --> 00:46:05,930
[THUNDERCLAP]
[DISTORTED CRY]

527
00:46:11,269 --> 00:46:14,188
[CHILDREN'S LAUGHTER]

528
00:46:17,525 --> 00:46:19,818
Don't die.

529
00:46:19,818 --> 00:46:22,113
[NEIGHING]

530
00:46:22,113 --> 00:46:23,281
[SNARLING]

531
00:46:23,281 --> 00:46:25,283
[WIND WHISTLING]

532
00:46:25,283 --> 00:46:27,784
MAN: You'll meet them again.
[SCREAMING]

533
00:46:27,784 --> 00:46:29,120
[NEIGHING]

534
00:46:29,120 --> 00:46:31,122
MAN:
Not yet.

535
00:46:32,123 --> 00:46:33,874
[MEN CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY]

536
00:46:33,874 --> 00:46:35,627
[MONKEY CHATTERING]

537
00:46:39,380 --> 00:46:43,092
No! They will clean it.
Wait and see.

538
00:46:45,595 --> 00:46:47,722
[CHATTERING]

539
00:46:52,935 --> 00:46:55,146
[♪♪♪]

540
00:47:10,662 --> 00:47:12,789
[GROWLING]

541
00:47:16,959 --> 00:47:18,919
Don't die.

542
00:47:18,919 --> 00:47:21,339
They'll feed you
to the lions.

543
00:47:21,339 --> 00:47:23,424
They are worth more
than we are.

544
00:47:34,018 --> 00:47:36,103
Better now?

545
00:47:36,103 --> 00:47:38,230
Clean.
You see?

546
00:47:38,230 --> 00:47:41,442
[MEN SPEAKING
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

547
00:47:43,444 --> 00:47:46,447
[SHOUTING]

548
00:47:48,407 --> 00:47:51,661
[ULULATING]

549
00:48:01,379 --> 00:48:03,798
[MEN CHATTERING]

550
00:48:08,720 --> 00:48:10,763
MAN:
Proximo!

551
00:48:10,763 --> 00:48:13,391
My old friend.

552
00:48:13,391 --> 00:48:16,811
Every day is a great day
when you are here.

553
00:48:16,811 --> 00:48:18,020
Today...

554
00:48:18,020 --> 00:48:21,440
is your
most fortunate day.

555
00:48:21,440 --> 00:48:23,735
[GROANS]

556
00:48:23,735 --> 00:48:26,153
Those giraffes
you sold me...

557
00:48:26,153 --> 00:48:28,364
they won't mate.
What?

558
00:48:28,364 --> 00:48:32,951
They just walk around
eating and not mating.

559
00:48:32,951 --> 00:48:36,581
You sold me
queer giraffes.

560
00:48:36,581 --> 00:48:38,499
I want my money back.

561
00:48:38,499 --> 00:48:40,835
Not a chance.
Aaarggh!

562
00:48:42,837 --> 00:48:44,963
I do special
price for you.

563
00:48:44,963 --> 00:48:46,549
On what?

564
00:48:48,300 --> 00:48:50,927
Have you seen my new stock?
Come and see them.

565
00:48:53,347 --> 00:48:55,558
[GRUNTS]

566
00:48:55,558 --> 00:48:58,227
[LOUD CHATTERING]

567
00:49:05,109 --> 00:49:07,944
Do any of them fight?
I've got a match coming up.

568
00:49:07,944 --> 00:49:10,656
Some are good for fighting,
others for dying.

569
00:49:10,656 --> 00:49:12,991
You need both, I think.

570
00:49:12,991 --> 00:49:14,744
Get up!

571
00:49:22,251 --> 00:49:24,169
What's your trade?

572
00:49:24,169 --> 00:49:26,255
I was a hunter.

573
00:49:26,255 --> 00:49:30,259
Oh, no. I bought him
from a salt mine in Carthage.

574
00:49:30,259 --> 00:49:31,469
Sit down!

575
00:49:36,140 --> 00:49:38,476
PROXIMO:
Mark of the legion.

576
00:49:38,476 --> 00:49:41,646
Deserter.
MAN: Maybe so. But who cares?

577
00:49:41,646 --> 00:49:43,898
He's a Spaniard.
PROXIMO: I'll take six...

578
00:49:43,898 --> 00:49:45,900
for 1,000.
MAN: One thousand?

579
00:49:45,900 --> 00:49:48,110
The Numidian alone
is worth 2,000!

580
00:49:48,110 --> 00:49:50,905
PROXIMO:
These slaves
are rotten.

581
00:49:50,905 --> 00:49:53,073
It all adds to the flavor.
No! No-no-no. Wait-wait.

582
00:49:53,073 --> 00:49:57,161
Wait!
We can negotiate.

583
00:49:57,161 --> 00:50:01,332
I'll give you 2,000...
and four for the beasts.

584
00:50:01,332 --> 00:50:03,960
That's 5,000
for an old friend.

585
00:50:05,377 --> 00:50:07,880
[MEN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

586
00:50:17,765 --> 00:50:21,185
[MULES BRAYING]

587
00:50:21,185 --> 00:50:24,062
Come on! How long does it take
to get into my own house?

588
00:50:24,062 --> 00:50:26,858
I am Proximo!

589
00:50:26,858 --> 00:50:30,026
I shall be closer to you
for the next few days,

590
00:50:30,026 --> 00:50:32,070
which will be last
of your miserable lives,

591
00:50:32,070 --> 00:50:33,656
than that bitch of a mother

592
00:50:33,656 --> 00:50:35,616
that brought you screaming
into this world!

593
00:50:35,616 --> 00:50:37,117
[MAN SHOUTING]

594
00:50:37,117 --> 00:50:40,538
I did not pay good money
for you for your company!

595
00:50:40,538 --> 00:50:44,458
I paid it so that I could
profit from your death.

596
00:50:44,458 --> 00:50:45,918
[SHRIEKING]

597
00:50:45,918 --> 00:50:49,755
And as your mother
was there at your beginning,

598
00:50:49,755 --> 00:50:53,217
so I shall be there
at your end.

599
00:50:53,217 --> 00:50:54,385
[SNARLING]

600
00:50:54,385 --> 00:50:57,889
And when you die,
and die you shall,

601
00:50:57,889 --> 00:51:00,850
your transition shall be
to the sound of:

602
00:51:00,850 --> 00:51:02,894
[CLAPPING]

603
00:51:05,855 --> 00:51:09,692
Gladiators,
I salute you.

604
00:51:11,777 --> 00:51:13,946
[MEN SHOUTING]

605
00:51:13,946 --> 00:51:16,782
MAN 1: Red!
MAN 2: Red.

606
00:51:16,782 --> 00:51:21,203
[GRUNTING]
Yellow!

607
00:51:21,203 --> 00:51:23,581
Yellow.

608
00:51:28,961 --> 00:51:30,880
[YELLS]

609
00:51:31,923 --> 00:51:33,131
Hyah!

610
00:51:33,131 --> 00:51:35,676
Good.

611
00:51:35,676 --> 00:51:37,135
Red.
Red!

612
00:51:41,682 --> 00:51:43,768
Spaniard!

613
00:52:00,534 --> 00:52:02,036
[GROANS]

614
00:52:08,459 --> 00:52:10,294
Unh!

615
00:52:10,294 --> 00:52:11,921
[FALCON SHRIEKS]

616
00:52:16,801 --> 00:52:19,553
PROXIMO:
That's enough
for the moment!

617
00:52:19,553 --> 00:52:21,013
His time will come.

618
00:52:23,057 --> 00:52:25,309
[SNICKERING]
Next!

619
00:52:38,572 --> 00:52:39,949
Spaniard,

620
00:52:39,949 --> 00:52:41,909
why don't you fight?

621
00:52:42,952 --> 00:52:44,536
We all have to fight.

622
00:52:58,926 --> 00:53:00,928
Is that the sign
of your gods?

623
00:53:03,221 --> 00:53:06,224
[CHUCKLES]

624
00:53:06,224 --> 00:53:08,102
Will that not anger them?

625
00:53:15,776 --> 00:53:19,864
[BULL BELLOWING]
[MAN SHOUTING]

626
00:53:29,748 --> 00:53:31,834
The gods favor you.

627
00:53:31,834 --> 00:53:34,837
Red is the gods' color.

628
00:53:34,837 --> 00:53:38,256
You will need
their help today.

629
00:53:45,056 --> 00:53:47,391
[CROWD CHEERING]

630
00:53:54,899 --> 00:53:58,610
Some of you are thinking
you won't fight.

631
00:53:58,610 --> 00:54:01,072
Some that you can't fight.

632
00:54:02,114 --> 00:54:04,491
They all say that,

633
00:54:04,491 --> 00:54:06,535
until they're out there.

634
00:54:08,495 --> 00:54:09,914
Listen.

635
00:54:09,914 --> 00:54:13,667
CROWD:
Kill. Kill. Kill.

636
00:54:19,548 --> 00:54:22,218
Thrust this
into another man's flesh,

637
00:54:22,218 --> 00:54:25,303
and then they will applaud
and love you for that.

638
00:54:25,303 --> 00:54:28,390
You--

639
00:54:28,390 --> 00:54:30,976
You may begin
to love them...

640
00:54:30,976 --> 00:54:33,229
for that.

641
00:54:36,982 --> 00:54:41,237
Ultimately,
we're all dead men.

642
00:54:42,905 --> 00:54:46,742
Sadly, we cannot
choose how, but...

643
00:54:46,742 --> 00:54:50,495
we can decide how
we meet that end...

644
00:54:50,495 --> 00:54:54,374
in order that
we are remembered...

645
00:54:54,374 --> 00:54:56,627
as men.

646
00:54:56,627 --> 00:54:58,545
[CHEERING CONTINUES]

647
00:54:58,545 --> 00:55:00,631
[MAN SHOUTING, INDISTINCTLY]

648
00:55:00,631 --> 00:55:03,508
MAN:
On the left,
draw your shields!

649
00:55:03,508 --> 00:55:06,137
On the right,
draw your swords!

650
00:55:06,137 --> 00:55:07,554
[BLACKSMITH POUNDING]

651
00:55:07,554 --> 00:55:09,807
CROWD:
Kill. Kill.

652
00:55:09,807 --> 00:55:13,978
Pair them up,
red with yellow.

653
00:55:13,978 --> 00:55:16,981
[POUNDING CONTINUES]

654
00:55:16,981 --> 00:55:18,398
Next!

655
00:55:21,819 --> 00:55:23,361
Next!

656
00:55:28,284 --> 00:55:30,119
[YELLS]

657
00:55:31,287 --> 00:55:33,205
[CROWD CHEERING]

658
00:55:40,254 --> 00:55:43,174
[GROWLING]

659
00:55:43,174 --> 00:55:45,383
[GROWLING CONTINUES]

660
00:55:49,805 --> 00:55:52,057
[WHIMPERING]

661
00:56:14,663 --> 00:56:17,166
[GRUNTING]
[CLANGING]

662
00:56:17,166 --> 00:56:19,793
[YELLING]

663
00:56:27,718 --> 00:56:30,012
[CROWD OOHING]

664
00:56:46,695 --> 00:56:48,697
[GRUNTS]
[SCREAMING]

665
00:56:56,205 --> 00:56:58,540
[CROWD CHEERING]

666
00:56:58,540 --> 00:57:00,292
[GRUNTING]

667
00:57:21,897 --> 00:57:23,815
[CLANGING]

668
00:57:53,178 --> 00:57:55,597
[YELLING]
[GRUNTS, GROANS]

669
00:57:59,226 --> 00:58:00,518
[GRUNTS]

670
00:58:02,854 --> 00:58:04,356
[CROWD ROARS]

671
00:58:19,455 --> 00:58:21,873
[CHEERING FADES]

672
00:58:30,841 --> 00:58:33,051
[♪♪♪]

673
00:58:42,518 --> 00:58:45,189
[MAN SHOUTING]

674
00:59:06,668 --> 00:59:09,421
Go away!
[ANGRY, INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

675
00:59:39,535 --> 00:59:42,662
He enters Rome
like a conquering hero.

676
00:59:42,662 --> 00:59:44,706
But what
has he conquered?

677
00:59:44,706 --> 00:59:47,792
Give him time, Gracchus.
He's young.

678
00:59:47,792 --> 00:59:49,878
I think he could do
very well.

679
00:59:49,878 --> 00:59:52,005
For Rome
or for you?

680
00:59:57,844 --> 01:00:00,722
GRACCHUS:
Go to your mother, Lucius.
It's what she'd like.

681
01:00:07,229 --> 01:00:08,813
Lucius!

682
01:00:08,813 --> 01:00:10,482
Mother!

683
01:00:12,150 --> 01:00:13,569
Hail, Caesar.

684
01:00:13,569 --> 01:00:15,153
Senators.

685
01:00:18,907 --> 01:00:21,868
Rome greets
her new emperor.

686
01:00:21,868 --> 01:00:25,414
Your loyal subjects
bid you welcome, Highness.

687
01:00:25,414 --> 01:00:28,917
Thank you, Falco.
And for the loyal subjects,

688
01:00:28,917 --> 01:00:32,670
I trust they weren't
too expensive.
Caesar.

689
01:00:32,670 --> 01:00:34,172
Gracchus.

690
01:00:34,172 --> 01:00:36,674
All Rome rejoices
in your return, Caesar.

691
01:00:36,674 --> 01:00:39,094
There are many matters
that require your attention.

692
01:00:42,473 --> 01:00:44,057
[CHATTERING, LAUGHING]

693
01:00:44,057 --> 01:00:45,683
MAN:
To order, then! To order!

694
01:00:45,683 --> 01:00:47,685
For your guidance, Caesar,

695
01:00:47,685 --> 01:00:50,355
the Senate has prepared
a series of protocols...

696
01:00:50,355 --> 01:00:51,773
to begin addressing

697
01:00:51,773 --> 01:00:53,817
the many problems
in the city.

698
01:00:53,817 --> 01:00:58,071
Beginning with basic sanitation
for the Greek quarter...

699
01:00:58,071 --> 01:01:01,325
to combat the plague which is
already springing up there.

700
01:01:01,325 --> 01:01:04,620
So if Caesar--
Shh.

701
01:01:05,703 --> 01:01:08,873
Don't you see,
Gracchus?

702
01:01:08,873 --> 01:01:11,335
That's the very problem,
isn't it?

703
01:01:11,335 --> 01:01:14,379
My father spent
all his time at study...

704
01:01:16,047 --> 01:01:20,051
At books and learning
and philosophy.

705
01:01:20,051 --> 01:01:25,098
He spent his twilight hours
reading scrolls from the Senate.

706
01:01:25,098 --> 01:01:28,519
And all the while,
the people have forgotten.

707
01:01:28,519 --> 01:01:31,021
But the Senate
is the People, sire.

708
01:01:31,021 --> 01:01:33,148
Chosen from among
the people

709
01:01:33,148 --> 01:01:34,899
to speak for the people.

710
01:01:34,899 --> 01:01:39,613
I doubt that many of the people
eat so well as you do, Gracchus.

711
01:01:39,613 --> 01:01:42,491
Or have such splendid
mistresses, Gaius.

712
01:01:42,491 --> 01:01:44,826
I think I understand
my own people.

713
01:01:44,826 --> 01:01:48,539
Then, perhaps Caesar will
be so good as to teach us...

714
01:01:48,539 --> 01:01:50,999
out of his own
extensive experience.

715
01:01:50,999 --> 01:01:54,670
[SENATORS LAUGHING]

716
01:01:54,670 --> 01:01:56,796
I call it love.
[CHUCKLING]

717
01:01:56,796 --> 01:02:00,800
I am their father.
The people are my children.

718
01:02:00,800 --> 01:02:03,303
And I shall hold them to my
bosom and embrace them tightly--

719
01:02:03,303 --> 01:02:04,638
Have you ever
embraced someone

720
01:02:04,638 --> 01:02:06,890
dying of plague,
sire?

721
01:02:12,479 --> 01:02:16,107
No. But if you
interrupt me again...

722
01:02:16,107 --> 01:02:18,151
I assure you
that you shall.

723
01:02:18,151 --> 01:02:21,071
Senator, my brother
is very tired.

724
01:02:21,071 --> 01:02:23,699
Leave your list
with me.

725
01:02:23,699 --> 01:02:26,702
Caesar shall do
all that Rome requires.

726
01:02:26,702 --> 01:02:29,329
My lady, as always,

727
01:02:29,329 --> 01:02:31,623
your lightest touch
commands obedience.

728
01:02:38,255 --> 01:02:41,007
Who are they
to lecture me?

729
01:02:41,007 --> 01:02:43,635
Commodus,
the Senate has its uses.

730
01:02:43,635 --> 01:02:46,430
What uses?
All they do is talk.

731
01:02:47,972 --> 01:02:50,934
It should be just...
you and me...

732
01:02:50,934 --> 01:02:53,978
and Rome.
Don't
even think it!

733
01:02:53,978 --> 01:02:56,022
There's always
been a Senate.

734
01:02:56,022 --> 01:02:57,982
Rome has changed.

735
01:02:57,982 --> 01:03:01,278
It takes an emperor
to rule an empire.

736
01:03:01,278 --> 01:03:03,488
Of course,
but leave the people their--

737
01:03:03,488 --> 01:03:05,532
Illusions.

738
01:03:05,532 --> 01:03:07,242
Traditions.

739
01:03:08,452 --> 01:03:11,747
My father's war
against the barbarians--

740
01:03:11,747 --> 01:03:13,749
He said it himself,
it achieved nothing.

741
01:03:13,749 --> 01:03:15,626
But the people
loved him.

742
01:03:15,626 --> 01:03:17,669
The people always
love victories.

743
01:03:17,669 --> 01:03:19,713
Why?

744
01:03:19,713 --> 01:03:22,674
They didn't see
the battles.

745
01:03:22,674 --> 01:03:24,718
What do they care
about Germania?

746
01:03:24,718 --> 01:03:26,844
They care about
the greatness of Rome.

747
01:03:26,844 --> 01:03:30,641
The greatness of Rome.

748
01:03:30,641 --> 01:03:32,684
Well, what is that?

749
01:03:35,103 --> 01:03:37,272
It's an idea.

750
01:03:37,272 --> 01:03:39,274
Greatness--

751
01:03:42,527 --> 01:03:44,488
Greatness is a vision.

752
01:03:44,488 --> 01:03:46,657
Exactly.
A vision.

753
01:03:47,616 --> 01:03:49,826
Do you not see,
Lucilla?

754
01:03:51,620 --> 01:03:53,330
I will give the people
a vision of Rome,

755
01:03:53,330 --> 01:03:55,957
and they'll love me
for it.

756
01:03:55,957 --> 01:03:59,127
And they'll soon forget
the tedious sermonizing

757
01:03:59,127 --> 01:04:01,129
of a few dry, old men.

758
01:04:11,723 --> 01:04:13,350
I will give the
people

759
01:04:13,350 --> 01:04:15,477
the greatest vision
of their lives.

760
01:04:36,247 --> 01:04:39,250
[DISTANT CHATTER]

761
01:04:44,506 --> 01:04:47,634
[HORNS BLOWING]

762
01:04:50,345 --> 01:04:53,181
[CROWD ROARING]

763
01:04:57,853 --> 01:05:00,146
[MEN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

764
01:05:05,402 --> 01:05:07,779
MAN:
Vino, vino, vino!
White and red wine

765
01:05:07,779 --> 01:05:09,531
for your drinking pleasure!

766
01:05:11,742 --> 01:05:14,035
Vino, vino, vino!
Red and white wine

767
01:05:14,035 --> 01:05:15,953
for your drinking pleasure!

768
01:05:17,414 --> 01:05:19,416
Games.

769
01:05:21,042 --> 01:05:24,254
One hundred and fifty days
of games.

770
01:05:24,254 --> 01:05:26,423
He's cleverer
than I thought.

771
01:05:26,423 --> 01:05:27,883
Oh, clever.

772
01:05:27,883 --> 01:05:30,677
The whole of Rome would
be laughing at him...

773
01:05:30,677 --> 01:05:33,012
if they weren't so afraid
of his Praetorians.

774
01:05:33,012 --> 01:05:35,432
Fear and wonder--
A powerful combination.

775
01:05:36,932 --> 01:05:39,895
You really think the people
will be seduced by that?

776
01:05:39,895 --> 01:05:44,190
I think he knows what Rome is.
Rome is the mob.

777
01:05:44,190 --> 01:05:47,527
Conjure magic for them,
and they'll be distracted.

778
01:05:47,527 --> 01:05:51,573
Take away their freedom
and still they'll roar.

779
01:05:51,573 --> 01:05:54,242
The beating heart
of Rome...

780
01:05:54,242 --> 01:05:56,536
is not the marble
of the Senate.

781
01:05:56,536 --> 01:05:59,038
It's the sand
of the Colosseum.

782
01:06:00,039 --> 01:06:02,417
He'll bring them death,

783
01:06:03,919 --> 01:06:06,880
and they will
love him for it.

784
01:06:06,880 --> 01:06:10,884
[MEN SHOUTING]
[HORSES NEIGHING]

785
01:06:10,884 --> 01:06:15,680
CROWD:
Spaniard! Spaniard!
Spaniard! Spaniard!

786
01:06:15,680 --> 01:06:17,140
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

787
01:06:17,140 --> 01:06:19,392
[CHILDREN CHATTERING
INDISTINCTLY]

788
01:06:21,227 --> 01:06:23,271
[METAL SCRAPING]

789
01:06:27,901 --> 01:06:30,612
Spaniard.
Spaniard.

790
01:06:30,612 --> 01:06:32,823
Spaniard.
Spaniard.

791
01:06:32,823 --> 01:06:36,033
Spaniard.
Spaniard.

792
01:06:37,577 --> 01:06:39,621
Guard!

793
01:06:40,914 --> 01:06:43,249
[CROWD ROARS]
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

794
01:06:53,384 --> 01:06:56,220
[GRUNTING]
[SWORDS CLANGING]

795
01:07:13,446 --> 01:07:15,907
[GROANING]

796
01:07:15,907 --> 01:07:18,409
[CROWD CLAMORING]

797
01:07:33,008 --> 01:07:35,343
[CROWD QUIETS]

798
01:07:40,640 --> 01:07:41,683
[GRUNTS]

799
01:07:42,851 --> 01:07:44,019
[CROWD GASPS]

800
01:07:44,019 --> 01:07:45,603
Are you not entertained?

801
01:07:45,603 --> 01:07:48,063
Are you not
entertained?

802
01:07:50,400 --> 01:07:53,110
Is this not
why you are here?

803
01:07:57,490 --> 01:08:01,036
MAN:
Spaniard! Spaniard!
Spaniard! Spaniard!

804
01:08:01,036 --> 01:08:05,707
CROWD [IN UNISON]:
Spaniard! Spaniard!
Spaniard! Spaniard!

805
01:08:08,251 --> 01:08:10,712
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

806
01:08:17,844 --> 01:08:19,596
What do you want?

807
01:08:19,596 --> 01:08:21,848
Hm?

808
01:08:21,848 --> 01:08:23,850
Girl?

809
01:08:23,850 --> 01:08:25,936
Boy?

810
01:08:25,936 --> 01:08:29,064
You sent for me?
Yes, I did.

811
01:08:29,064 --> 01:08:32,525
You're good, Spaniard,
but you're not that good.

812
01:08:32,525 --> 01:08:34,402
You could be
magnificent.

813
01:08:34,402 --> 01:08:36,529
I'm required to kill,
so I kill.

814
01:08:36,529 --> 01:08:38,113
That is enough.

815
01:08:38,113 --> 01:08:40,115
That's enough
for the provinces,

816
01:08:40,115 --> 01:08:41,826
but not for Rome.

817
01:08:43,995 --> 01:08:46,414
[SQUEALS]
The young emperor...

818
01:08:46,414 --> 01:08:49,375
has arranged
a series of spectacles

819
01:08:49,375 --> 01:08:53,797
to commemorate his father,
Marcus Aurelius.

820
01:08:53,797 --> 01:08:55,840
I find that amusing...

821
01:08:55,840 --> 01:08:57,968
since it was
Marcus Aurelius--

822
01:08:57,968 --> 01:09:00,261
the wise, the all-knowing
Marcus Aurelius

823
01:09:00,261 --> 01:09:01,972
--that closed us down.

824
01:09:01,972 --> 01:09:03,264
[LION GROWLING]

825
01:09:05,600 --> 01:09:09,562
So finally, after five years
of scratching a living

826
01:09:09,562 --> 01:09:12,315
in flea-infested
villages,

827
01:09:12,315 --> 01:09:15,568
we're finally going back
to where we belong,

828
01:09:15,568 --> 01:09:17,821
the Colosseum.

829
01:09:17,821 --> 01:09:22,659
[INHALING]
Oh, you should see
the Colosseum, Spaniard.

830
01:09:23,701 --> 01:09:26,997
Fifty thousand Romans...

831
01:09:26,997 --> 01:09:31,001
watching every movement
of your sword,

832
01:09:31,001 --> 01:09:35,130
willing you to make
that killer blow.

833
01:09:35,130 --> 01:09:37,381
[WHISPERING]
The silence before
you strike...

834
01:09:37,381 --> 01:09:40,217
and the noise afterwards,

835
01:09:40,217 --> 01:09:43,346
it rises.
It rises up like--

836
01:09:43,346 --> 01:09:47,558
Like th--
Like a storm...

837
01:09:47,558 --> 01:09:49,811
As if you were
the thunder god himself.

838
01:09:49,811 --> 01:09:51,855
You were a gladiator?

839
01:09:51,855 --> 01:09:53,731
Yes, I was.

840
01:09:59,863 --> 01:10:01,698
You won your freedom?

841
01:10:01,698 --> 01:10:05,451
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
A long time ago,
the emperor...

842
01:10:05,451 --> 01:10:08,038
presented me
with a rudius.

843
01:10:08,038 --> 01:10:11,041
It's just
a wooden sword.

844
01:10:12,458 --> 01:10:16,880
The symbol of your freedom.
He--

845
01:10:16,880 --> 01:10:19,757
He touched me on the shoulder,
and I was free.

846
01:10:19,757 --> 01:10:21,551
[LAUGHS]

847
01:10:21,551 --> 01:10:23,720
You knew Marcus Aurelius?

848
01:10:23,720 --> 01:10:25,680
I did not say I knew him.

849
01:10:25,680 --> 01:10:28,474
I said he touched me
on the shoulder once.

850
01:10:28,474 --> 01:10:30,393
You asked me
what I want.

851
01:10:32,228 --> 01:10:34,856
I too want to stand
in front of the emperor...

852
01:10:36,066 --> 01:10:38,151
as you did.

853
01:10:38,151 --> 01:10:42,155
Then, listen to me.
Learn from me.

854
01:10:42,155 --> 01:10:46,325
I wasn't the best
because I killed quickly.

855
01:10:46,325 --> 01:10:49,996
I was the best
because the crowd loved me.

856
01:10:49,996 --> 01:10:53,624
Win the crowd,
and you'll win your freedom.

857
01:10:57,754 --> 01:10:59,714
I will win the crowd.

858
01:11:01,966 --> 01:11:05,178
I will give them something
they have never seen before.

859
01:11:05,178 --> 01:11:06,554
Ha!

860
01:11:06,554 --> 01:11:10,183
So, Spaniard, we shall go
to Rome together...

861
01:11:10,183 --> 01:11:12,351
and have
bloody adventures.

862
01:11:12,351 --> 01:11:14,437
And the great whore
will suckle us until we are...

863
01:11:14,437 --> 01:11:16,814
fat and happy and
can suckle no more.

864
01:11:16,814 --> 01:11:19,150
And then,

865
01:11:19,150 --> 01:11:21,360
when enough men
have died,

866
01:11:23,071 --> 01:11:25,322
perhaps you will
have your freedom.

867
01:11:29,577 --> 01:11:33,456
Here.
Use this.

868
01:11:45,593 --> 01:11:47,929
[MEN LAUGHING,
CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY]

869
01:11:55,853 --> 01:11:57,772
It's somewhere
out there--

870
01:11:57,772 --> 01:12:02,652
My country,
my home.

871
01:12:02,652 --> 01:12:06,363
My wife
is preparing food.

872
01:12:06,363 --> 01:12:09,993
My daughters carry
water from the river.

873
01:12:09,993 --> 01:12:12,203
Will I ever
see them again?

874
01:12:12,203 --> 01:12:14,538
I think no.

875
01:12:14,538 --> 01:12:17,667
Do you believe you'll see
them again when you die?

876
01:12:17,667 --> 01:12:19,961
I think so.

877
01:12:19,961 --> 01:12:24,465
But then,
I will die soon.

878
01:12:24,465 --> 01:12:26,717
They will not die
for many years.

879
01:12:26,717 --> 01:12:29,804
I'll have to wait.

880
01:12:29,804 --> 01:12:32,431
But you would...
wait.

881
01:12:32,431 --> 01:12:34,100
Of course.

882
01:12:35,893 --> 01:12:38,354
You see,

883
01:12:38,354 --> 01:12:43,318
my wife...
and my son...

884
01:12:43,318 --> 01:12:45,528
are already
waiting for me.

885
01:12:45,528 --> 01:12:48,114
You'll meet them again.

886
01:12:48,114 --> 01:12:51,159
But not yet.

887
01:12:54,162 --> 01:12:57,456
Not yet.
Unless--

888
01:12:57,456 --> 01:12:59,250
Not yet.

889
01:13:02,253 --> 01:13:03,838
Not yet.

890
01:13:04,922 --> 01:13:07,675
[THUNDERCLAP]

891
01:13:07,675 --> 01:13:09,886
[♪♪♪]

892
01:13:13,556 --> 01:13:15,225
[CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY]

893
01:13:15,225 --> 01:13:17,434
[♪♪♪]

894
01:13:32,575 --> 01:13:34,244
[CROWD CHEERING]

895
01:13:34,244 --> 01:13:36,037
[MEN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

896
01:14:06,859 --> 01:14:08,485
MAN:
Out!

897
01:14:09,612 --> 01:14:11,906
Go, go. Out!

898
01:14:13,657 --> 01:14:15,492
[CROWD ROARING IN DISTANCE]

899
01:14:15,492 --> 01:14:17,078
[MAN SHOUTING]

900
01:14:24,001 --> 01:14:26,212
PROXIMO:
Good to see you again,
old friend.

901
01:14:31,384 --> 01:14:33,469
[WHISPERING]
Bring me fortune.

902
01:14:34,387 --> 01:14:36,431
[MAN SHOUTING]

903
01:14:38,099 --> 01:14:41,518
Have you ever seen
anything like that before?

904
01:14:41,518 --> 01:14:42,937
[CROWD EXCLAIMING]

905
01:14:42,937 --> 01:14:45,522
I didn't know men could
build such things.

906
01:14:45,522 --> 01:14:47,650
[BIRDS TWEETING]

907
01:14:54,324 --> 01:14:56,742
Win the crowd.

908
01:14:56,742 --> 01:15:00,330
MAN:
Get Inside! Move. Inside.

909
01:15:03,833 --> 01:15:06,627
[BIRD COOING]

910
01:15:06,627 --> 01:15:09,755
[BREATHING SOFTLY]

911
01:15:49,586 --> 01:15:52,756
He sleeps so well
because he's loved.

912
01:15:55,134 --> 01:15:57,887
Come, brother.
It's late.

913
01:16:00,806 --> 01:16:03,976
I will make Rome
the wonder of the ages.

914
01:16:06,312 --> 01:16:09,564
That is what Gracchus and his
friends don't understand.

915
01:16:09,564 --> 01:16:11,442
All my desires

916
01:16:11,442 --> 01:16:14,320
are splitting
my head to pieces.

917
01:16:20,743 --> 01:16:23,371
Commodus,
drink this tonic.

918
01:16:32,463 --> 01:16:35,799
I think the time
is almost right.

919
01:16:35,799 --> 01:16:38,469
I could announce the dissolution
of the Senate...

920
01:16:38,469 --> 01:16:40,555
at the celebration
to honor our father.

921
01:16:40,555 --> 01:16:43,640
You think I should?

922
01:16:43,640 --> 01:16:45,726
Are the people ready?

923
01:16:47,228 --> 01:16:49,355
I think you need
your rest now.

924
01:16:55,778 --> 01:16:57,696
Will you stay with me?

925
01:16:57,696 --> 01:16:59,740
Still afraid of the dark,
brother?

926
01:17:07,081 --> 01:17:08,707
Still.

927
01:17:08,707 --> 01:17:11,419
[CHUCKLING]
Always.

928
01:17:13,045 --> 01:17:14,505
Stay with me tonight?

929
01:17:14,505 --> 01:17:16,090
You know I won't.

930
01:17:19,802 --> 01:17:21,845
Then kiss me.

931
01:17:30,854 --> 01:17:32,648
Sleep, brother.

932
01:17:40,823 --> 01:17:42,950
[CHUCKLES]

933
01:17:51,041 --> 01:17:53,544
MAN:
Come on now.
Get out of the way!

934
01:17:58,382 --> 01:18:01,135
I want you. I want you.
I want you so--

935
01:18:01,135 --> 01:18:03,638
SOLDIER:
All right,
Let him pass!

936
01:18:03,638 --> 01:18:05,848
[TRUMPETING]

937
01:18:08,601 --> 01:18:10,685
[CROWD ROARING]

938
01:18:19,654 --> 01:18:22,072
[BETTORS CLAMORING]
MAN: Sixty!

939
01:18:22,072 --> 01:18:23,824
MAN:
Five hundred!

940
01:18:25,742 --> 01:18:27,370
The emperor
wants battles,

941
01:18:27,370 --> 01:18:29,288
and I don't want to
sacrifice my best fighters.

942
01:18:29,288 --> 01:18:30,665
The crowd wants
battles,

943
01:18:30,665 --> 01:18:32,500
so the emperor
gives them battles.

944
01:18:32,500 --> 01:18:34,918
And you get
the battle of Carthage.

945
01:18:34,918 --> 01:18:36,753
The massacre
of Carthage.

946
01:18:36,753 --> 01:18:38,005
Guten Tag.

947
01:18:38,005 --> 01:18:39,965
Oh, why don't you go down
to the prison

948
01:18:39,965 --> 01:18:42,009
and round up all the
beggars and thieves.

949
01:18:42,009 --> 01:18:43,886
We've done that.

950
01:18:43,886 --> 01:18:45,762
If you want to give away
the best gladiators

951
01:18:45,762 --> 01:18:47,473
in the whole of the
empire,

952
01:18:47,473 --> 01:18:49,392
then I want
double the rates.

953
01:18:49,392 --> 01:18:51,143
You'll get
your contract rates,

954
01:18:51,143 --> 01:18:53,229
or you'll get
your contract canceled.

955
01:18:53,229 --> 01:18:54,938
You don't like it?

956
01:18:54,938 --> 01:18:56,940
Then you can crawl
back down that shit-hole

957
01:18:56,940 --> 01:18:59,610
that you came from.

958
01:19:00,528 --> 01:19:01,778
[CHATTERING]

959
01:19:01,778 --> 01:19:03,738
MAN:
Cassius, please!
Please, Cassius!

960
01:19:33,686 --> 01:19:36,397
Gladiator, are you the one
they call the Spaniard?

961
01:19:36,397 --> 01:19:38,190
Yes.

962
01:19:38,190 --> 01:19:41,444
They said
you were a giant.

963
01:19:41,444 --> 01:19:43,738
They said you could crush a
man's skull with one hand.

964
01:19:43,738 --> 01:19:46,949
A man's? No.

965
01:19:46,949 --> 01:19:50,703
A boy's.

966
01:19:50,703 --> 01:19:52,663
They have
good horses in Spain?

967
01:19:52,663 --> 01:19:54,915
Some of the best.

968
01:19:54,915 --> 01:19:59,462
This is Argento,
and this is Scarto.

969
01:19:59,462 --> 01:20:02,423
They were my horses.

970
01:20:02,423 --> 01:20:04,634
They were
taken from me.

971
01:20:04,634 --> 01:20:06,719
I like you, Spaniard.

972
01:20:06,719 --> 01:20:08,471
I shall cheer for you.

973
01:20:08,471 --> 01:20:10,139
They let you watch the games?

974
01:20:10,139 --> 01:20:12,182
My uncle says
it makes me strong.

975
01:20:12,182 --> 01:20:13,559
And what does your father say?

976
01:20:13,559 --> 01:20:15,394
My father's dead.

977
01:20:17,062 --> 01:20:20,107
Master Lucius,
it is time.

978
01:20:20,107 --> 01:20:21,817
I have to go.

979
01:20:21,817 --> 01:20:24,278
Your name is Lucius?

980
01:20:25,446 --> 01:20:28,532
Lucius Verus,
after my father.

981
01:20:40,753 --> 01:20:44,381
[LION ROARING]

982
01:20:44,381 --> 01:20:47,092
[MAN SHOUTING ORDERS
INDISTINCTLY]

983
01:20:47,092 --> 01:20:49,470
[EQUIPMENT RUMBLING]

984
01:20:50,845 --> 01:20:54,183
[MEN CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY]

985
01:20:58,312 --> 01:21:00,606
MAN:
Lower!

986
01:21:05,611 --> 01:21:07,613
MAN: Claudius!
MAN 2: Yes?

987
01:21:08,781 --> 01:21:10,282
MAN:
More shields!

988
01:21:23,420 --> 01:21:26,215
[METAL CLANGING]

989
01:21:29,844 --> 01:21:32,680
HANDLER:
When the emperor enters,

990
01:21:32,680 --> 01:21:34,973
raise your weapons,
salute him,

991
01:21:34,973 --> 01:21:38,101
and then
speak together!

992
01:21:38,101 --> 01:21:42,189
Face the emperor and don't
turn your back on him!

993
01:21:42,189 --> 01:21:46,151
Go, and die with honor!

994
01:21:46,151 --> 01:21:48,571
[MEN YELLING]

995
01:22:01,208 --> 01:22:05,838
[CROWD REACTION BUILDS]

996
01:22:05,838 --> 01:22:08,215
[CROWD ROARING]

997
01:22:40,539 --> 01:22:43,166
MAN:
Hail, mighty Caesar!

998
01:22:43,166 --> 01:22:47,296
CROWD:
Caesar! Caesar! Caesar!

999
01:22:47,296 --> 01:22:49,924
Caesar! Caesar! Caesar!

1000
01:22:53,009 --> 01:22:55,846
[IN UNISON]
And we who are about to die,
salute you!

1001
01:22:57,848 --> 01:23:00,142
CASSIUS:
On this day,

1002
01:23:00,142 --> 01:23:04,020
we reach back
to hallowed antiquity...

1003
01:23:04,020 --> 01:23:07,524
to bring you a recreation
of the second fall

1004
01:23:07,524 --> 01:23:09,819
of mighty Carthage!

1005
01:23:09,819 --> 01:23:11,862
[CROWD CHEERING]

1006
01:23:13,697 --> 01:23:18,619
On the barren
plain of Zarma,

1007
01:23:18,619 --> 01:23:22,080
there stood
the invincible armies...

1008
01:23:22,080 --> 01:23:25,334
of the barbarian, Hannibal.

1009
01:23:25,334 --> 01:23:28,504
Ferocious
mercenaries and warriors

1010
01:23:28,504 --> 01:23:31,173
from all brute nations

1011
01:23:31,173 --> 01:23:34,468
bent on merciless...

1012
01:23:34,468 --> 01:23:38,221
destruction...conquest.

1013
01:23:38,221 --> 01:23:42,351
Your emperor
is pleased to give you

1014
01:23:42,351 --> 01:23:45,312
the barbarian horde!

1015
01:23:45,312 --> 01:23:47,272
[CROWD ROARS]

1016
01:23:49,399 --> 01:23:51,694
[CHEERING CONTINUES]

1017
01:23:54,070 --> 01:23:55,990
Anyone here been
in the army?

1018
01:23:55,990 --> 01:23:57,658
No.
MAN: Yes.

1019
01:23:57,658 --> 01:23:59,451
I served with you
at Vindobona.

1020
01:23:59,451 --> 01:24:02,412
You can help me.

1021
01:24:02,412 --> 01:24:06,291
Whatever comes
out of these gates,

1022
01:24:06,291 --> 01:24:09,169
we've got a better chance
of survival if we work together.

1023
01:24:09,169 --> 01:24:11,254
Do you understand?

1024
01:24:13,549 --> 01:24:16,468
If we stay together,
we survive.

1025
01:24:16,468 --> 01:24:19,388
I'm pleased to bring you
the legionnaires

1026
01:24:19,388 --> 01:24:23,893
of Scipio Africanus!

1027
01:24:23,893 --> 01:24:27,270
[CHEERING]

1028
01:24:29,398 --> 01:24:31,734
[CONFUSED SHOUTING]

1029
01:24:33,736 --> 01:24:35,362
To the death!

1030
01:24:39,033 --> 01:24:42,077
[CROWD CHANTING AND SHOUTING,
INDISTINCTLY]

1031
01:24:45,831 --> 01:24:47,541
MAXIMUS:
Stay close!

1032
01:24:53,255 --> 01:24:54,590
Come together!

1033
01:24:55,549 --> 01:24:56,967
[GROANS]

1034
01:24:56,967 --> 01:24:58,176
Staggered columns!

1035
01:24:58,176 --> 01:25:00,345
Staggered columns!

1036
01:25:03,265 --> 01:25:05,559
[CROWD "OOHS"]

1037
01:25:09,063 --> 01:25:10,940
[GROANS, SCREAMS]

1038
01:25:12,232 --> 01:25:14,234
MAN 1:
Soon all your men
will be slain.

1039
01:25:14,234 --> 01:25:16,236
MAN 2:
You don't have a chance!

1040
01:25:21,867 --> 01:25:23,285
[GIGGLING]

1041
01:25:27,247 --> 01:25:29,165
MAXIMUS:
Lock your shields!
Stay as one!

1042
01:25:29,165 --> 01:25:31,043
[SHOUTING]

1043
01:25:31,043 --> 01:25:32,544
Hold!

1044
01:25:34,755 --> 01:25:36,256
Hold!

1045
01:25:36,256 --> 01:25:38,425
As one!
[IN UNISON]
As one!

1046
01:25:40,803 --> 01:25:42,471
Well done!

1047
01:25:45,557 --> 01:25:46,725
Hyah! Hyah!

1048
01:25:50,562 --> 01:25:52,982
[MIXED CHEERS, BOOS]

1049
01:25:54,024 --> 01:25:55,692
Hold!

1050
01:25:55,692 --> 01:25:58,612
Diamond! Diamond!

1051
01:26:03,283 --> 01:26:05,077
Yes!
[GASPS]

1052
01:26:08,831 --> 01:26:10,916
[GRUNTS]
[GROANS]

1053
01:26:12,001 --> 01:26:13,543
Aaarggh!
[GRUNTS]

1054
01:26:16,880 --> 01:26:18,799
Hagen!
[GROANS]

1055
01:26:24,013 --> 01:26:25,263
Aah!

1056
01:26:38,819 --> 01:26:40,529
[CROWD GROANS]

1057
01:26:42,238 --> 01:26:44,700
This column to the chariots!
This column--

1058
01:26:44,700 --> 01:26:46,535
Stay with me!
[GRUNTING]

1059
01:26:49,371 --> 01:26:51,289
MAXIMUS:
Quickly!

1060
01:26:51,289 --> 01:26:53,834
Get out there!
Hurry!

1061
01:26:55,544 --> 01:26:57,212
[YELLING]

1062
01:26:57,212 --> 01:26:59,923
[GRUNTING]
[GROANING]

1063
01:26:59,923 --> 01:27:01,133
[YELLING]

1064
01:27:35,375 --> 01:27:37,502
Maximus!

1065
01:27:40,296 --> 01:27:42,049
[MOCKINGLY]
Ooh-ooh, ooh-ooh.

1066
01:27:48,847 --> 01:27:50,933
Single column!
Single column!

1067
01:27:50,933 --> 01:27:52,642
GLADIATORS:
Single column!

1068
01:27:59,399 --> 01:28:01,484
[YELLS]
[CROWD ROARS]

1069
01:28:01,484 --> 01:28:02,736
[SCOFFS]

1070
01:28:16,708 --> 01:28:18,460
[LAUGHING]

1071
01:28:26,969 --> 01:28:29,512
[CROWD ROARS APPROVAL]

1072
01:28:32,099 --> 01:28:34,143
[BELLOWS]

1073
01:28:34,143 --> 01:28:36,645
[JUBA'S YELLS CONTINUE]

1074
01:28:36,645 --> 01:28:37,896
We win!

1075
01:28:37,896 --> 01:28:39,522
[OVATION CONTINUES]

1076
01:28:43,152 --> 01:28:46,655
My history's
a little hazy, Cassius,

1077
01:28:46,655 --> 01:28:49,658
but shouldn't the barbarians
lose the battle of Carthage?

1078
01:28:49,658 --> 01:28:51,952
Uh, yes, sire.

1079
01:28:51,952 --> 01:28:54,288
Um, forgive me, sire.

1080
01:28:54,288 --> 01:28:58,167
COMMODUS:
No, I rather enjoy surprises.

1081
01:28:58,167 --> 01:28:59,626
Who is he?

1082
01:28:59,626 --> 01:29:03,337
They call him
the Spaniard, sire.

1083
01:29:04,547 --> 01:29:06,091
I think I'll meet him.

1084
01:29:06,091 --> 01:29:08,135
Yes, sire.

1085
01:29:09,385 --> 01:29:12,388
MAN:
Hail to the barbarians!

1086
01:29:16,643 --> 01:29:18,812
[HORN FANFARE]

1087
01:29:27,487 --> 01:29:30,782
MAN:
Forward! Arms at ready!

1088
01:29:43,753 --> 01:29:45,463
Drop your weapons!

1089
01:29:49,634 --> 01:29:53,263
Gladiator, the emperor
has asked for you.

1090
01:29:53,263 --> 01:29:55,389
I'm at the emperor's
service.

1091
01:30:00,854 --> 01:30:03,690
[CROWD CHEERS]

1092
01:30:22,125 --> 01:30:24,627
Rise. Rise.

1093
01:30:33,929 --> 01:30:36,265
Your fame is
well deserved, Spaniard.

1094
01:30:36,265 --> 01:30:39,017
I don't think there's ever
been a gladiator to match you.

1095
01:30:39,017 --> 01:30:40,685
As for this young man,

1096
01:30:40,685 --> 01:30:42,771
he insists
you are Hector reborn.

1097
01:30:42,771 --> 01:30:44,606
Or was it Hercules?

1098
01:30:44,606 --> 01:30:46,524
Why doesn't the hero
reveal himself

1099
01:30:46,524 --> 01:30:48,610
and tell us all
your real name?

1100
01:30:50,528 --> 01:30:52,155
You do have a name?

1101
01:30:53,115 --> 01:30:55,284
My name is Gladiator.

1102
01:30:57,869 --> 01:30:59,829
How dare you
show your back to me?

1103
01:30:59,829 --> 01:31:01,039
[CROWD MURMURING]

1104
01:31:01,039 --> 01:31:03,292
Slave!

1105
01:31:03,292 --> 01:31:05,501
You will remove your helmet
and tell me your name.

1106
01:31:17,222 --> 01:31:20,225
My name is
Maximus Decimus Meridius,

1107
01:31:20,225 --> 01:31:22,644
commander of the armies
of the north,

1108
01:31:22,644 --> 01:31:25,479
general
of the Felix Legions,

1109
01:31:25,479 --> 01:31:29,943
loyal servant to the true
emperor, Marcus Aurelius,

1110
01:31:29,943 --> 01:31:32,446
father to
a murdered son,

1111
01:31:32,446 --> 01:31:35,449
husband to
a murdered wife...

1112
01:31:35,449 --> 01:31:37,451
and I will have my
vengeance...

1113
01:31:37,451 --> 01:31:39,202
in this life or
the next.

1114
01:31:46,251 --> 01:31:47,710
Arms!

1115
01:31:48,878 --> 01:31:51,673
[CROWD CLAMORING]

1116
01:31:59,848 --> 01:32:04,311
CROWD:
Live! Live! Live!

1117
01:32:04,311 --> 01:32:07,730
Live! Live! Live!
Live! Live! Live!

1118
01:32:10,150 --> 01:32:12,319
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

1119
01:32:18,574 --> 01:32:20,534
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

1120
01:32:31,296 --> 01:32:33,340
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

1121
01:32:36,634 --> 01:32:39,012
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

1122
01:32:45,477 --> 01:32:48,688
[CROWD ROARS]

1123
01:32:51,066 --> 01:32:54,903
Guards,
at rest!

1124
01:32:54,903 --> 01:32:56,821
[CHEERING CONTINUES]

1125
01:32:56,821 --> 01:32:59,573
[♪♪♪]

1126
01:33:40,698 --> 01:33:43,659
[RHYTHMIC BANGING]

1127
01:33:43,659 --> 01:33:46,829
GLADIATORS [IN UNISON]:
Maximus! Maximus!
Maximus! Maximus!

1128
01:33:55,046 --> 01:33:57,132
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

1129
01:34:15,150 --> 01:34:18,487
Why is he
still alive?

1130
01:34:18,487 --> 01:34:20,654
I don't know.

1131
01:34:20,654 --> 01:34:22,991
He shouldn't
be alive.

1132
01:34:22,991 --> 01:34:25,910
It vexes me.

1133
01:34:25,910 --> 01:34:28,913
I'm terribly vexed.

1134
01:34:38,840 --> 01:34:40,883
I did what I had to do.

1135
01:34:40,883 --> 01:34:43,094
If Father had had
his way,

1136
01:34:43,094 --> 01:34:45,763
the empire would
have been torn apart.

1137
01:34:45,763 --> 01:34:48,016
You do see that?

1138
01:34:48,016 --> 01:34:50,059
Yes.

1139
01:34:53,687 --> 01:34:57,192
What did you feel
when you saw him?

1140
01:34:59,361 --> 01:35:02,364
I felt nothing.

1141
01:35:02,364 --> 01:35:05,325
He wounded you deeply,
didn't he?

1142
01:35:06,368 --> 01:35:09,871
No more than
I wounded him.

1143
01:35:13,249 --> 01:35:15,460
They lied to me
in Germania.

1144
01:35:16,752 --> 01:35:19,005
They told me
he was dead.

1145
01:35:21,090 --> 01:35:24,052
If they lie to me,
they don't respect me.

1146
01:35:24,052 --> 01:35:26,762
If they don't respect me,
how can they ever love me?

1147
01:35:28,598 --> 01:35:31,059
Then you must
let the legions know...

1148
01:35:31,059 --> 01:35:35,021
their treachery
will not go unpunished.

1149
01:35:35,021 --> 01:35:38,816
Poor sister, I wouldn't
want to be your enemy.

1150
01:35:40,485 --> 01:35:42,195
What will you do?

1151
01:35:55,041 --> 01:35:56,167
This way!

1152
01:36:28,908 --> 01:36:32,036
[GATE CLOSES]

1153
01:36:32,036 --> 01:36:33,288
Rich matrons pay well

1154
01:36:33,288 --> 01:36:35,206
to be pleasured by
the bravest champions.

1155
01:36:35,206 --> 01:36:38,209
I knew your brother
would send assassins.

1156
01:36:38,209 --> 01:36:40,962
I didn't realize
he would send his best.

1157
01:36:42,422 --> 01:36:45,174
Maximus,
he doesn't know.

1158
01:36:45,174 --> 01:36:47,093
My family was burned
and crucified

1159
01:36:47,093 --> 01:36:49,178
while they were
still alive.

1160
01:36:49,178 --> 01:36:51,681
I knew nothing--
Don't lie to me!

1161
01:36:57,853 --> 01:36:59,147
I wept for them.

1162
01:36:59,147 --> 01:37:01,983
As you wept
for your father?

1163
01:37:01,983 --> 01:37:04,068
As you wept for
your father?

1164
01:37:04,068 --> 01:37:07,863
I have been living in
a prison of fear since that day.

1165
01:37:07,863 --> 01:37:09,449
To be unable
to mourn your father

1166
01:37:09,449 --> 01:37:12,535
for fear
of your brother.

1167
01:37:12,535 --> 01:37:15,455
To live in terror
every moment of every day

1168
01:37:15,455 --> 01:37:17,749
because your son
is heir to the throne.

1169
01:37:19,959 --> 01:37:23,212
Oh, I have wept.

1170
01:37:23,212 --> 01:37:26,466
My son was innocent.

1171
01:37:26,466 --> 01:37:29,051
So is mine.

1172
01:37:30,553 --> 01:37:33,515
Must my son die too,
before you will trust me?

1173
01:37:35,517 --> 01:37:39,437
What does it matter
if I trust you or not?

1174
01:37:39,437 --> 01:37:42,398
The gods have spared you.
Don't you understand?

1175
01:37:42,398 --> 01:37:44,192
Today I saw a slave
become more powerful

1176
01:37:44,192 --> 01:37:45,777
than the
emperor of Rome.

1177
01:37:45,777 --> 01:37:47,696
The gods
have spared me?

1178
01:37:47,696 --> 01:37:51,407
I am at their mercy, with the
power only to amuse a mob!

1179
01:37:51,407 --> 01:37:54,703
That is power.
The mob is Rome.

1180
01:37:54,703 --> 01:37:56,538
And while Commodus
controls them,

1181
01:37:56,538 --> 01:37:57,789
he controls everything.

1182
01:37:58,748 --> 01:38:00,792
Listen to me.

1183
01:38:00,792 --> 01:38:04,003
My brother has enemies,
most of all in the Senate.

1184
01:38:04,003 --> 01:38:06,589
But while
the people follow him,

1185
01:38:06,589 --> 01:38:09,801
no one would dare
stand up to him until you.

1186
01:38:09,801 --> 01:38:13,012
They oppose him,
yet they do nothing.

1187
01:38:13,012 --> 01:38:14,472
There are some politicians

1188
01:38:14,472 --> 01:38:16,558
who have dedicated
their lives to Rome.

1189
01:38:16,558 --> 01:38:19,352
One man above all.

1190
01:38:19,352 --> 01:38:22,731
If I can arrange it,
will you meet him?

1191
01:38:22,731 --> 01:38:24,982
Do you not understand?

1192
01:38:24,982 --> 01:38:26,401
I may die in this
cell tonight,

1193
01:38:26,401 --> 01:38:29,195
or in the arena tomorrow.
I am a slave!

1194
01:38:29,195 --> 01:38:31,865
What possible
difference can I make?

1195
01:38:31,865 --> 01:38:34,534
This man wants
what you want.

1196
01:38:34,534 --> 01:38:37,453
Then have him
kill Commodus!

1197
01:38:39,330 --> 01:38:42,083
I knew a man once,

1198
01:38:42,083 --> 01:38:45,670
a noble man,
a man of principle

1199
01:38:45,670 --> 01:38:47,963
who loved my father.

1200
01:38:47,963 --> 01:38:51,300
And my father
loved him.

1201
01:38:51,300 --> 01:38:54,888
This man
served Rome well.

1202
01:38:58,683 --> 01:39:01,018
That man is gone.

1203
01:39:01,018 --> 01:39:03,563
Your brother
did his work well.

1204
01:39:03,563 --> 01:39:05,899
Let me help you.

1205
01:39:11,320 --> 01:39:15,157
Yes, you can
help me.

1206
01:39:17,702 --> 01:39:19,953
Forget you
ever knew me...

1207
01:39:19,953 --> 01:39:22,081
and never
come here again.

1208
01:39:25,042 --> 01:39:28,588
Guard! The lady
has finished with me.

1209
01:39:29,798 --> 01:39:31,925
[GATE OPENS]

1210
01:39:33,676 --> 01:39:36,011
[CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY]

1211
01:39:39,891 --> 01:39:42,268
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

1212
01:39:42,268 --> 01:39:44,604
[HISSING]

1213
01:39:44,604 --> 01:39:45,897
[SHOUTS]

1214
01:39:56,031 --> 01:40:00,411
Maximus,
you commanded legions?

1215
01:40:00,411 --> 01:40:02,037
You had many victories?

1216
01:40:02,037 --> 01:40:03,790
Yes.

1217
01:40:03,790 --> 01:40:05,082
In Germania?

1218
01:40:06,459 --> 01:40:08,544
In many countries.

1219
01:40:10,254 --> 01:40:11,965
MAN:
General.

1220
01:40:29,899 --> 01:40:32,902
[MEN CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY]

1221
01:40:38,282 --> 01:40:41,536
[GAGGING]

1222
01:40:42,537 --> 01:40:45,957
[LAUGHING]

1223
01:40:54,131 --> 01:40:56,175
[SIGHS]

1224
01:41:00,555 --> 01:41:03,016
You have a great name.

1225
01:41:03,016 --> 01:41:06,019
He must kill your name
before he kills you.

1226
01:41:07,896 --> 01:41:10,231
[TRUMPETING]

1227
01:41:15,444 --> 01:41:17,363
Yes, at the far end.

1228
01:41:17,363 --> 01:41:19,949
Senator Gaius.
Hello.

1229
01:41:19,949 --> 01:41:23,870
Senator Gracchus.
Don't often see you

1230
01:41:23,870 --> 01:41:26,915
enjoying the pleasures
of the vulgar crowd.

1231
01:41:26,915 --> 01:41:29,542
I don't pretend to be a man
of the people, Senator.

1232
01:41:29,542 --> 01:41:32,795
But I do try to be a man
for the people.

1233
01:41:32,795 --> 01:41:35,214
[CHEERING]

1234
01:41:46,601 --> 01:41:50,438
CROWD:
Caesar! Caesar! Caesar!

1235
01:41:50,438 --> 01:41:52,523
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

1236
01:41:58,279 --> 01:42:00,615
CASSIUS:
People of Rome!

1237
01:42:02,575 --> 01:42:05,578
On the fourth day
of Antioch,

1238
01:42:05,578 --> 01:42:09,540
we can celebrate
the 64th day of the games.

1239
01:42:09,540 --> 01:42:15,755
And, in his
majestic charity,

1240
01:42:15,755 --> 01:42:20,301
the Emperor has deigned this day
to favor the people of Rome...

1241
01:42:20,301 --> 01:42:24,555
with an historical
final match.

1242
01:42:24,555 --> 01:42:26,975
Returning to
the Colosseum today...

1243
01:42:26,975 --> 01:42:31,562
after five years
in retirement, Caesar

1244
01:42:31,562 --> 01:42:35,524
is pleased to bring you
the only

1245
01:42:35,524 --> 01:42:37,902
undefeated champion

1246
01:42:37,902 --> 01:42:40,237
in Roman history,

1247
01:42:40,237 --> 01:42:45,660
the legendary
Tigris of Gaul!

1248
01:42:45,660 --> 01:42:48,203
[CHEERING]

1249
01:42:57,713 --> 01:43:00,549
[HORSES NEIGHING]

1250
01:43:00,549 --> 01:43:02,844
Whoa! Whoa!

1251
01:43:06,597 --> 01:43:10,267
He knows too well
how to manipulate the mob.

1252
01:43:10,267 --> 01:43:13,104
Marcus Aurelius had a dream
that was Rome, Proximo.

1253
01:43:13,104 --> 01:43:15,564
This is not it!
This is not it!

1254
01:43:15,564 --> 01:43:18,233
Marcus Aurelius
is dead, Maximus.

1255
01:43:18,233 --> 01:43:21,487
We mortals are but
shadows and dust.

1256
01:43:21,487 --> 01:43:25,033
Shadows and dust,
Maximus!

1257
01:43:25,033 --> 01:43:28,452
CASSIUS:
Representing the training lyceum
of Antonius Proximo,

1258
01:43:28,452 --> 01:43:32,247
Caesar is proud
to give you...

1259
01:43:32,247 --> 01:43:35,626
Aelius Maximus!

1260
01:43:35,626 --> 01:43:38,587
[CROWD CHEERING]

1261
01:43:38,587 --> 01:43:41,007
[TRUMPETING]

1262
01:43:41,007 --> 01:43:44,760
CROWD:
Maximus! Maximus! Maximus!

1263
01:43:49,057 --> 01:43:51,517
They embrace him like
he's one of their own.

1264
01:43:51,517 --> 01:43:55,104
The mob is fickle, brother.
He'll be forgotten in a month.

1265
01:43:55,104 --> 01:43:58,107
CROWD:
Maximus! Maximus! Maximus!

1266
01:43:58,107 --> 01:44:01,110
No, much sooner
than that.

1267
01:44:02,862 --> 01:44:05,447
It's been arranged.

1268
01:44:05,447 --> 01:44:09,035
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

1269
01:44:10,870 --> 01:44:14,456
CROWD:
Maximus! Maximus!
Maximus!

1270
01:44:17,334 --> 01:44:19,962
[THUNDEROUS CHEERING]

1271
01:44:23,091 --> 01:44:25,968
We who are about to die
salute you.

1272
01:44:25,968 --> 01:44:29,513
[CHEERING]

1273
01:44:29,513 --> 01:44:32,016
MAN:
We're with you, Maximus!

1274
01:44:52,578 --> 01:44:55,414
[GRUNTING]

1275
01:44:58,751 --> 01:45:00,753
[GROWLING]

1276
01:45:05,925 --> 01:45:08,343
[SNARLING]

1277
01:45:08,343 --> 01:45:10,805
[GRUNTING]

1278
01:45:13,515 --> 01:45:16,269
MAN:
Come on, finish it!

1279
01:45:18,437 --> 01:45:21,190
[GRUNTING]

1280
01:45:23,442 --> 01:45:25,444
[GROWLING]

1281
01:45:30,323 --> 01:45:32,827
[ROARING]

1282
01:45:32,827 --> 01:45:34,829
[GRUNTING]

1283
01:45:37,748 --> 01:45:40,626
[GRUNTING]

1284
01:45:42,128 --> 01:45:44,046
No!

1285
01:45:44,046 --> 01:45:45,380
Pull! Pull!

1286
01:45:48,968 --> 01:45:51,304
[GRUNTING]

1287
01:45:53,430 --> 01:45:55,390
[GROWLING]

1288
01:45:59,854 --> 01:46:01,230
[GROWLING]

1289
01:46:01,230 --> 01:46:02,439
[YELLING]

1290
01:46:04,733 --> 01:46:06,777
[ROARS]

1291
01:46:06,777 --> 01:46:08,029
Yeah!

1292
01:46:17,830 --> 01:46:20,333
Loose! Loose!
Loose! Loose!

1293
01:46:24,086 --> 01:46:26,672
[ROARING]

1294
01:46:28,507 --> 01:46:30,301
[CROWD CHEERING]

1295
01:46:30,301 --> 01:46:32,803
[GRUNTING]

1296
01:46:34,972 --> 01:46:36,140
Aah!

1297
01:46:40,978 --> 01:46:42,271
Aah!

1298
01:46:43,647 --> 01:46:45,733
[SCREAMING]

1299
01:46:47,776 --> 01:46:49,528
Gut him!
Kill him!

1300
01:46:49,528 --> 01:46:53,406
CROWD:
Kill! Kill!
Kill! Kill!

1301
01:46:56,409 --> 01:46:59,080
[GRUNTS]

1302
01:47:01,749 --> 01:47:04,377
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

1303
01:47:11,050 --> 01:47:14,095
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

1304
01:47:14,095 --> 01:47:15,971
Kill!
Kill!

1305
01:47:15,971 --> 01:47:17,265
Kill!

1306
01:47:17,265 --> 01:47:18,640
Kill!

1307
01:47:39,995 --> 01:47:41,914
[CHEERING]

1308
01:47:49,004 --> 01:47:52,007
[MIXED CHEERING AND BOOING]

1309
01:47:53,634 --> 01:47:56,971
MAN:
Maximus!
Maximus the Merciful!

1310
01:47:56,971 --> 01:48:00,141
[CROWD LAUGHING AND CHEERING]

1311
01:48:06,688 --> 01:48:10,025
CROWD:
Maximus! Maximus!
Maximus!

1312
01:48:18,200 --> 01:48:22,163
MAN:
Forward, guards!
On battery!

1313
01:48:22,163 --> 01:48:24,206
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

1314
01:48:24,206 --> 01:48:26,875
[SNARLING]

1315
01:48:26,875 --> 01:48:30,838
CROWD:
Maximus! Maximus!
Maximus!

1316
01:48:37,928 --> 01:48:41,265
[JEERING AND BOOING]

1317
01:48:51,317 --> 01:48:55,654
What am I going
to do with you?

1318
01:48:55,654 --> 01:48:58,324
You simply won't...

1319
01:48:58,324 --> 01:49:00,326
die.

1320
01:49:03,871 --> 01:49:07,082
Are we so different,
you and I?

1321
01:49:07,082 --> 01:49:09,626
You take life
when you have to...

1322
01:49:09,626 --> 01:49:11,628
as I do.

1323
01:49:11,628 --> 01:49:14,131
I have only one more
life to take.

1324
01:49:14,131 --> 01:49:15,757
Then it is done.

1325
01:49:15,757 --> 01:49:17,968
Then take it now.

1326
01:49:24,766 --> 01:49:26,935
[WIND BLOWING]

1327
01:49:30,647 --> 01:49:33,317
They tell me
your son...

1328
01:49:33,317 --> 01:49:35,777
squealed
like a girl...

1329
01:49:35,777 --> 01:49:38,739
when they nailed him
to the cross.

1330
01:49:38,739 --> 01:49:43,536
And your wife...
moaned like a whore...

1331
01:49:45,454 --> 01:49:47,622
when they ravaged her...

1332
01:49:47,622 --> 01:49:50,000
again and again...

1333
01:49:51,293 --> 01:49:53,295
and again.

1334
01:49:58,050 --> 01:50:01,762
The time for honoring yourself
will soon be at an end,

1335
01:50:06,475 --> 01:50:08,769
Highness.

1336
01:50:09,853 --> 01:50:12,064
[♪♪♪]

1337
01:50:16,402 --> 01:50:19,947
[THUNDEROUS CHEERING]

1338
01:50:19,947 --> 01:50:25,286
CROWD:
Maximus! Maximus!
Maximus!

1339
01:50:34,836 --> 01:50:38,340
General! General!

1340
01:50:38,340 --> 01:50:40,342
General!

1341
01:50:40,342 --> 01:50:43,137
General! General!
Get back!

1342
01:50:43,137 --> 01:50:45,806
General!
Cicero!

1343
01:50:45,806 --> 01:50:47,141
Maximus! Maximus!

1344
01:50:48,767 --> 01:50:52,062
[CROWD CONTINUES CHANTING]
CICERO: General!

1345
01:50:52,062 --> 01:50:53,772
General.
Where are you camped?

1346
01:50:53,772 --> 01:50:55,983
Ostia.

1347
01:50:57,359 --> 01:51:01,572
Maximus! Maximus!
Maximus! Maximus!

1348
01:51:01,572 --> 01:51:04,533
We love you, Maximus!
Praise the victor!

1349
01:51:04,533 --> 01:51:07,244
Tell the men their general
lives. Find me.

1350
01:51:07,244 --> 01:51:08,703
Move along!
Find me!

1351
01:51:10,539 --> 01:51:15,127
[CROWD CONTINUES CHANTING]

1352
01:51:34,647 --> 01:51:36,982
Can they hear you?

1353
01:51:39,818 --> 01:51:42,029
Who?

1354
01:51:42,029 --> 01:51:44,990
Your family,
in the afterlife.

1355
01:51:46,450 --> 01:51:49,077
Oh, yes.
What do you say to them?

1356
01:51:52,747 --> 01:51:55,250
To my boy,

1357
01:51:55,250 --> 01:51:57,503
I tell him I will
see him again soon,

1358
01:51:57,503 --> 01:52:02,007
to keep his heels down
when he's riding his horse.

1359
01:52:03,592 --> 01:52:05,594
To my wife--

1360
01:52:07,471 --> 01:52:09,931
That is not
your business.

1361
01:52:09,931 --> 01:52:12,434
[CHUCKLING]

1362
01:52:16,980 --> 01:52:20,192
And now they love Maximus
for his mercy.

1363
01:52:21,860 --> 01:52:23,404
So I can't just kill him,

1364
01:52:23,404 --> 01:52:26,615
or it makes me even
more unmerciful!

1365
01:52:26,615 --> 01:52:31,036
The whole thing's
like some crazed nightmare.

1366
01:52:31,953 --> 01:52:34,540
FALCO:
He is defying you.

1367
01:52:34,540 --> 01:52:37,585
His every victory
is an act of defiance.

1368
01:52:37,585 --> 01:52:41,714
The mob sees this,
and so do the Senate.

1369
01:52:41,714 --> 01:52:46,134
Every day he lives,
they grow bolder.

1370
01:52:46,134 --> 01:52:48,387
Kill him.
No.

1371
01:52:49,846 --> 01:52:52,558
I will not make
a martyr of him.

1372
01:52:58,272 --> 01:53:00,441
I have been told...

1373
01:53:00,441 --> 01:53:02,484
of a certain sea snake...

1374
01:53:02,484 --> 01:53:06,779
which has a very unusual method
of attracting its prey.

1375
01:53:06,779 --> 01:53:10,492
It will lie at the bottom
of the ocean as if wounded.

1376
01:53:10,492 --> 01:53:13,870
Then its enemies
will approach,

1377
01:53:13,870 --> 01:53:16,957
and yet it will
lie quite still.

1378
01:53:16,957 --> 01:53:21,253
And then its enemies
will take little bites of it,

1379
01:53:21,253 --> 01:53:23,756
and yet it remains...

1380
01:53:23,756 --> 01:53:26,300
still.

1381
01:53:27,676 --> 01:53:30,137
So...

1382
01:53:30,137 --> 01:53:32,805
we will lie still...

1383
01:53:32,805 --> 01:53:36,518
and let our enemies
come to us and nibble.

1384
01:53:36,518 --> 01:53:39,980
Have every senator followed.

1385
01:53:39,980 --> 01:53:41,898
[SHOUTING]

1386
01:53:49,156 --> 01:53:51,575
[PEOPLE CLAMORING]

1387
01:53:52,909 --> 01:53:54,869
Maximus.

1388
01:53:56,330 --> 01:53:58,457
Cicero,
my old friend.

1389
01:53:58,457 --> 01:54:00,501
I thought perhaps
I'd seen you for the last time.

1390
01:54:00,501 --> 01:54:03,629
I thought
you were dead.
Close.

1391
01:54:03,629 --> 01:54:05,422
How long have the men
been in Ostia?

1392
01:54:05,422 --> 01:54:06,799
All winter.

1393
01:54:06,799 --> 01:54:08,425
And how do they look?

1394
01:54:08,425 --> 01:54:10,761
Fattened and bored.

1395
01:54:10,761 --> 01:54:12,513
Who's in command?

1396
01:54:12,513 --> 01:54:15,265
Some fool
from Rome.

1397
01:54:15,265 --> 01:54:17,392
How soon do you think they
could be ready to fight?

1398
01:54:17,392 --> 01:54:19,144
For you, tomorrow.

1399
01:54:20,771 --> 01:54:23,398
I need you to
do something for me.

1400
01:54:23,398 --> 01:54:26,067
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

1401
01:54:27,611 --> 01:54:29,154
MAN:
Come see. Witness.

1402
01:54:29,154 --> 01:54:30,989
If you haven't
been in the arena,

1403
01:54:30,989 --> 01:54:32,700
you can see the show here.

1404
01:54:32,700 --> 01:54:35,536
Giant Maximus is defeating
our Emperor Commodus.

1405
01:54:35,536 --> 01:54:37,204
What are we
to do?

1406
01:54:37,204 --> 01:54:39,998
He's defying everyone
by doing this...

1407
01:54:39,998 --> 01:54:41,625
[FARTING]
[FIRE ROARS]

1408
01:54:41,625 --> 01:54:42,876
Oh, my goodness!

1409
01:54:42,876 --> 01:54:44,169
[GIGGLING]

1410
01:54:44,169 --> 01:54:45,337
Oh, he got him!

1411
01:54:45,337 --> 01:54:47,088
GUARD:
Make way!

1412
01:54:47,088 --> 01:54:49,299
Give way! Give way!

1413
01:54:52,010 --> 01:54:54,763
MAN:
Three casks of red wine...

1414
01:54:54,763 --> 01:54:57,349
My lady? I served
your father at Vindobona.

1415
01:54:57,349 --> 01:54:59,309
GUARD: Back.
CICERO: My lady.

1416
01:54:59,309 --> 01:55:01,395
I served your father
at Vindobona.

1417
01:55:01,395 --> 01:55:04,105
Back!
And I served
the General Maximus.

1418
01:55:04,105 --> 01:55:06,608
I serve him still.

1419
01:55:06,608 --> 01:55:08,569
Stop.

1420
01:55:08,569 --> 01:55:10,821
Stop.
GUARD: Stop!

1421
01:55:10,821 --> 01:55:12,989
LUCILLA:
Stand back.

1422
01:55:14,115 --> 01:55:15,617
The General sends
word.

1423
01:55:15,617 --> 01:55:17,494
He will meet
your politician.

1424
01:55:18,995 --> 01:55:20,622
For your loyalty,
soldier.

1425
01:55:20,622 --> 01:55:22,624
Thank you,
my lady.

1426
01:55:22,624 --> 01:55:23,792
Up!

1427
01:55:31,966 --> 01:55:34,595
LUCILLA:
Leave us.

1428
01:55:39,140 --> 01:55:41,101
Senator Gracchus.

1429
01:55:54,406 --> 01:55:55,616
General.

1430
01:55:57,075 --> 01:56:01,037
I hope my coming here today
is evidence enough that...

1431
01:56:01,037 --> 01:56:03,081
you can trust me.

1432
01:56:06,710 --> 01:56:09,463
The Senate is with you?
The Senate?

1433
01:56:11,214 --> 01:56:14,718
Yes. I can
speak for them.

1434
01:56:14,718 --> 01:56:18,179
You can buy my freedom
and smuggle me out of Rome?

1435
01:56:18,179 --> 01:56:21,141
To what end?

1436
01:56:21,141 --> 01:56:23,184
Get me outside
the city walls.

1437
01:56:23,184 --> 01:56:25,437
Have fresh horses ready
to take me to Ostia.

1438
01:56:25,437 --> 01:56:27,397
My army's
encamped there.

1439
01:56:27,397 --> 01:56:29,399
By nightfall of the
second day,

1440
01:56:29,399 --> 01:56:31,443
I shall return
at the head of 5,000 men.

1441
01:56:31,443 --> 01:56:33,528
But the legions
all have new commanders...

1442
01:56:33,528 --> 01:56:35,155
loyal to Commodus.

1443
01:56:35,155 --> 01:56:36,782
Let my men
see me alive,

1444
01:56:36,782 --> 01:56:38,867
and you shall see where
their loyalties lie.

1445
01:56:38,867 --> 01:56:40,577
This is madness.

1446
01:56:40,577 --> 01:56:42,579
No Roman army
has entered the capital

1447
01:56:42,579 --> 01:56:44,456
in a hundred years.
Gracchus--

1448
01:56:44,456 --> 01:56:46,416
I will not trade
one dictatorship for another!

1449
01:56:46,416 --> 01:56:50,712
The time for half-measures
and talk is over, Senator.

1450
01:56:50,712 --> 01:56:54,716
And after your
glorious coup, what then?

1451
01:56:54,716 --> 01:56:58,553
You'll take your
5,000 warriors and leave?

1452
01:56:58,553 --> 01:57:00,931
I will leave.

1453
01:57:00,931 --> 01:57:02,891
The soldiers will stay
for your protection,

1454
01:57:02,891 --> 01:57:04,726
under the command
of the Senate.

1455
01:57:04,726 --> 01:57:08,104
So once all
of Rome is yours,

1456
01:57:08,104 --> 01:57:11,065
you'll just give it
back to the people?

1457
01:57:11,065 --> 01:57:13,151
Tell me why.

1458
01:57:18,824 --> 01:57:21,535
Because that was the
last wish of a dying man.

1459
01:57:24,997 --> 01:57:27,207
I will kill Commodus.

1460
01:57:28,834 --> 01:57:32,379
The fate of Rome
I leave to you.

1461
01:57:33,755 --> 01:57:36,424
Marcus Aurelius
trusted you.

1462
01:57:37,801 --> 01:57:40,345
His daughter
trusts you.

1463
01:57:43,807 --> 01:57:45,934
I will trust you.

1464
01:57:45,934 --> 01:57:48,562
But we have
little time.

1465
01:57:48,562 --> 01:57:50,772
Give me two days...

1466
01:57:50,772 --> 01:57:54,026
and I will
buy your freedom.

1467
01:57:54,026 --> 01:57:56,904
And you--

1468
01:57:56,904 --> 01:57:59,907
You stay alive.

1469
01:57:59,907 --> 01:58:02,116
Or I'll be dead.

1470
01:58:03,451 --> 01:58:05,537
Now we must go.

1471
01:58:10,042 --> 01:58:12,836
It won't work.

1472
01:58:12,836 --> 01:58:15,380
The Emperor
knows too much.

1473
01:58:15,380 --> 01:58:17,298
And as for me,

1474
01:58:19,259 --> 01:58:21,428
it's becoming
dangerous.

1475
01:58:22,429 --> 01:58:24,973
You will be paid
on my return.

1476
01:58:26,641 --> 01:58:28,894
I give you my word.
[CHUCKLES]

1477
01:58:28,894 --> 01:58:31,730
Your word?
What if you don't return?

1478
01:58:31,730 --> 01:58:35,358
Do you remember what it was
to have trust, Proximo?

1479
01:58:35,358 --> 01:58:37,819
Trust?

1480
01:58:41,155 --> 01:58:43,366
Who am I to trust?

1481
01:58:43,366 --> 01:58:45,326
I will kill Commodus.

1482
01:58:45,326 --> 01:58:47,996
Why would I
want that?

1483
01:58:47,996 --> 01:58:49,998
He makes me rich.

1484
01:58:52,500 --> 01:58:54,878
Oh, I--

1485
01:58:54,878 --> 01:58:58,090
I know that you are
a man of your word, General.

1486
01:58:59,466 --> 01:59:02,176
I know that you
would die for honor.

1487
01:59:03,344 --> 01:59:06,264
You would
die for Rome.

1488
01:59:06,264 --> 01:59:08,809
You would die for
the memory of your ancestors.

1489
01:59:08,809 --> 01:59:11,603
But I,
on the other hand...

1490
01:59:14,439 --> 01:59:16,608
...am an entertainer.

1491
01:59:18,485 --> 01:59:21,113
Hm?
Guard!

1492
01:59:25,533 --> 01:59:28,078
He killed the man
who set you free.

1493
01:59:30,872 --> 01:59:33,333
[GEESE HONKING]

1494
01:59:34,668 --> 01:59:37,462
[♪♪♪]

1495
01:59:37,462 --> 01:59:39,756
Praetorians, master.

1496
01:59:45,637 --> 01:59:47,722
Halt!

1497
01:59:57,607 --> 01:59:59,776
COMMODUS:
Where have you been?

1498
01:59:59,776 --> 02:00:01,778
I sent for you.

1499
02:00:02,863 --> 02:00:04,906
Please, brother.

1500
02:00:09,285 --> 02:00:11,579
What's troubling
you?

1501
02:00:14,582 --> 02:00:17,127
Does Gracchus
have a new lover?

1502
02:00:18,712 --> 02:00:20,755
I don't know.

1503
02:00:21,923 --> 02:00:23,967
I thought
you'd seen him.

1504
02:00:25,385 --> 02:00:29,389
He infects everyone
like a putrid fever.

1505
02:00:29,389 --> 02:00:31,850
For the health of Rome,
the Senate must be bled.

1506
02:00:33,101 --> 02:00:35,269
And he will bleed too...

1507
02:00:35,269 --> 02:00:37,898
very soon.

1508
02:00:38,982 --> 02:00:41,275
But not tonight.

1509
02:00:55,165 --> 02:00:57,625
Do you remember what
our father said once?

1510
02:00:59,794 --> 02:01:01,796
"It's a dream...

1511
02:01:03,548 --> 02:01:06,176
a frightful dream...

1512
02:01:07,969 --> 02:01:09,429
life is."

1513
02:01:12,099 --> 02:01:14,475
Do you think that's true?

1514
02:01:14,475 --> 02:01:16,937
I don't know.

1515
02:01:19,731 --> 02:01:21,775
I think it is.

1516
02:01:24,236 --> 02:01:26,988
And I have only you
to share it with.

1517
02:02:04,692 --> 02:02:06,778
Open your mouth.

1518
02:02:35,932 --> 02:02:38,350
[SIGHS DEEPLY]

1519
02:02:43,106 --> 02:02:45,275
You know I love you.

1520
02:02:47,319 --> 02:02:49,654
And I love you.

1521
02:03:10,633 --> 02:03:13,469
[DOG BARKING IN DISTANCE]

1522
02:03:18,016 --> 02:03:20,894
[GATE OPENS]

1523
02:03:25,190 --> 02:03:27,734
Out.
Get out!

1524
02:03:27,734 --> 02:03:30,237
Move!

1525
02:03:34,199 --> 02:03:36,368
Congratulations,
General.

1526
02:03:36,368 --> 02:03:39,913
You've got very...
persuasive friends.

1527
02:03:45,210 --> 02:03:47,879
My brother's had
Gracchus arrested.

1528
02:03:47,879 --> 02:03:51,423
We daren't wait any longer.
You must leave tonight.

1529
02:03:51,423 --> 02:03:55,762
Proximo will come at midnight
and take you to the gate.

1530
02:03:55,762 --> 02:03:58,723
Your servant, Cicero, will be
waiting there with horses.

1531
02:04:01,184 --> 02:04:03,186
You have done
all this?

1532
02:04:03,186 --> 02:04:06,189
Yes.
You risk too much.

1533
02:04:07,439 --> 02:04:09,984
I have much
to pay for.

1534
02:04:11,652 --> 02:04:13,780
You have nothing
to pay for.

1535
02:04:13,780 --> 02:04:17,367
You love your son.
You're strong for him.

1536
02:04:20,370 --> 02:04:23,664
I am tired
of being strong.

1537
02:04:23,664 --> 02:04:24,791
[SIGHS]

1538
02:04:24,791 --> 02:04:27,001
My brother hates
all the world,

1539
02:04:27,001 --> 02:04:29,129
and you
most of all.

1540
02:04:29,129 --> 02:04:33,174
Because your father
chose me.
No.

1541
02:04:33,174 --> 02:04:36,594
Because my father
loved you.

1542
02:04:40,056 --> 02:04:43,059
And because
I loved you.

1543
02:04:45,145 --> 02:04:47,272
A long time ago.

1544
02:04:51,234 --> 02:04:53,527
Was I very different then?

1545
02:05:00,118 --> 02:05:02,120
You laughed more.

1546
02:05:06,040 --> 02:05:08,793
I have felt alone
all my life,

1547
02:05:08,793 --> 02:05:10,920
except with you.

1548
02:05:14,466 --> 02:05:16,176
I must go.

1549
02:05:16,176 --> 02:05:18,178
Yes.

1550
02:05:45,788 --> 02:05:47,665
LUCIUS:
There. There.

1551
02:05:47,665 --> 02:05:48,958
[WOOD CLACKING]

1552
02:05:48,958 --> 02:05:51,461
There. There. There.
There. There. There.

1553
02:05:55,965 --> 02:05:57,717
[GIGGLING]

1554
02:05:57,717 --> 02:06:00,387
There. There.
And I've got you.

1555
02:06:03,056 --> 02:06:05,433
Isn't it late to be
playing legionnaire?

1556
02:06:05,433 --> 02:06:07,894
I'm not
a legionnaire.

1557
02:06:07,894 --> 02:06:10,355
Not a legionnaire?
I'm a gladiator.

1558
02:06:11,856 --> 02:06:13,358
A gladiator?

1559
02:06:13,358 --> 02:06:15,818
Gladiators only fight
in the games.

1560
02:06:15,818 --> 02:06:17,862
Wouldn't you rather be

1561
02:06:17,862 --> 02:06:20,114
a great Roman warrior
like Julius Caesar?

1562
02:06:20,114 --> 02:06:23,201
I'm Maximus,
the savior of Rome!

1563
02:06:25,619 --> 02:06:27,621
The savior of Rome?

1564
02:06:35,422 --> 02:06:37,631
And who said that?

1565
02:06:37,631 --> 02:06:39,342
[INDISTINCT WHISPERING]

1566
02:06:45,597 --> 02:06:47,141
Where's Lucius?

1567
02:06:48,435 --> 02:06:50,603
He's with the Emperor,
my lady.

1568
02:06:54,148 --> 02:06:56,234
LUCIUS: She couldn't.
COMMODUS: Yes, she did.

1569
02:06:56,234 --> 02:06:58,278
She took it
from a basket...

1570
02:06:59,446 --> 02:07:01,364
and pressed it
to her breast,

1571
02:07:01,364 --> 02:07:03,241
right here
above her heart.

1572
02:07:03,241 --> 02:07:05,076
[COMMODUS HISSES]

1573
02:07:05,076 --> 02:07:07,537
LUCIUS:
It bit her in the breast?

1574
02:07:07,537 --> 02:07:09,414
Yes.

1575
02:07:09,414 --> 02:07:12,666
You see, Lucius,
sometimes royal ladies

1576
02:07:12,666 --> 02:07:15,295
behave very strangely

1577
02:07:15,295 --> 02:07:17,255
and do very odd things
in the name of love.

1578
02:07:17,255 --> 02:07:20,467
I think it's
silly.
So do I.

1579
02:07:21,759 --> 02:07:23,844
So do I.

1580
02:07:23,844 --> 02:07:26,180
Sister, join us.

1581
02:07:26,180 --> 02:07:28,099
I've been reading
to dear Lucius.

1582
02:07:28,099 --> 02:07:29,934
LUCIUS:
I've been
reading too.

1583
02:07:29,934 --> 02:07:31,185
Yes.

1584
02:07:31,185 --> 02:07:33,271
He's a very clever
little boy.

1585
02:07:33,271 --> 02:07:36,483
He'll make a grand
emperor one day.

1586
02:07:36,483 --> 02:07:38,485
We've been reading about
the great Mark Antony

1587
02:07:38,485 --> 02:07:40,111
and his adventures
in Egypt.

1588
02:07:40,111 --> 02:07:42,238
The queen killed herself
with a snake.

1589
02:07:42,238 --> 02:07:45,741
COMMODUS:
And just wait until you hear
what happened to our ancestors.

1590
02:07:45,741 --> 02:07:48,202
If you're very good,

1591
02:07:48,202 --> 02:07:50,497
tomorrow night I'll
tell you the story

1592
02:07:50,497 --> 02:07:52,248
of Emperor Claudius.

1593
02:07:52,248 --> 02:07:55,001
He was betrayed...

1594
02:07:55,001 --> 02:07:57,378
by those
closest to him.

1595
02:07:58,630 --> 02:08:00,672
By his own blood.

1596
02:08:02,300 --> 02:08:04,676
They whispered
in dark corners...

1597
02:08:04,676 --> 02:08:06,887
and went out
late at night...

1598
02:08:06,887 --> 02:08:09,474
and conspired...

1599
02:08:09,474 --> 02:08:11,518
and conspired.

1600
02:08:13,186 --> 02:08:14,979
But the
Emperor Claudius

1601
02:08:14,979 --> 02:08:17,148
knew that they were
up to something.

1602
02:08:17,148 --> 02:08:19,651
He knew they were
busy little bees.

1603
02:08:21,694 --> 02:08:23,321
And one night

1604
02:08:23,321 --> 02:08:25,323
he sat down
with one of them...

1605
02:08:25,323 --> 02:08:27,992
and he looked
at her...

1606
02:08:27,992 --> 02:08:30,995
and he said,

1607
02:08:30,995 --> 02:08:34,248
"Tell me what
you've been doing,

1608
02:08:34,248 --> 02:08:36,250
busy little bee,

1609
02:08:38,294 --> 02:08:41,673
or I shall strike down
those dearest to you.

1610
02:08:41,673 --> 02:08:46,052
You shall watch
as I bathe in their blood."

1611
02:08:49,096 --> 02:08:51,765
And the Emperor
was heartbroken.

1612
02:08:53,643 --> 02:08:56,187
The little bee
had wounded him more deeply

1613
02:08:56,187 --> 02:08:59,399
than anyone else
could ever have done.

1614
02:09:00,733 --> 02:09:04,904
And what do you think
happened then, Lucius?

1615
02:09:04,904 --> 02:09:07,198
I don't know, Uncle.

1616
02:09:12,744 --> 02:09:15,081
The little bee
told him everything.

1617
02:09:19,126 --> 02:09:21,546
[DISTANT BARKING]

1618
02:09:32,014 --> 02:09:34,141
[HISSING]

1619
02:09:34,141 --> 02:09:36,352
[♪♪♪]

1620
02:09:38,563 --> 02:09:40,565
[HORSE NEIGHS]

1621
02:09:54,662 --> 02:09:58,583
MAN:
Open, in the name
of the Emperor!

1622
02:09:58,583 --> 02:10:00,460
Proximo!

1623
02:10:00,460 --> 02:10:04,088
Open the gates in the name
of the Emperor!

1624
02:10:04,088 --> 02:10:08,008
Proximo!
[GATES RATTLING]

1625
02:10:08,008 --> 02:10:09,719
Open the gates!

1626
02:10:09,719 --> 02:10:11,512
[RATTLING CONTINUES]

1627
02:10:15,475 --> 02:10:18,144
Open the gates,
Proximo!

1628
02:10:18,144 --> 02:10:21,481
Do you want to die,
old man?

1629
02:10:21,481 --> 02:10:23,274
Here.

1630
02:10:23,274 --> 02:10:26,068
Everything
is prepared.

1631
02:10:26,068 --> 02:10:29,196
It seems you've won
your freedom.
Proximo,

1632
02:10:29,196 --> 02:10:31,949
are you in danger
of becoming a good man?

1633
02:10:32,659 --> 02:10:33,867
Ha!

1634
02:10:36,704 --> 02:10:40,750
Juba?
All enemies of
the Emperor, die!

1635
02:10:40,750 --> 02:10:45,004
Open the gates!
The Emperor commands!

1636
02:10:48,800 --> 02:10:51,010
Pull!

1637
02:10:53,012 --> 02:10:56,015
Move! Two columns
on the left!

1638
02:10:59,185 --> 02:11:02,104
I only need moments, so do not
be careless with your lives.

1639
02:11:02,104 --> 02:11:04,106
If you don't want
any part of this,

1640
02:11:04,106 --> 02:11:05,566
go back to your cells.

1641
02:11:05,566 --> 02:11:07,527
We'll wait here
for you, Maximus.

1642
02:11:07,527 --> 02:11:09,069
ALL:
Strength and honor.

1643
02:11:09,069 --> 02:11:10,404
Go!

1644
02:11:11,531 --> 02:11:13,240
Strength and honor.

1645
02:11:15,702 --> 02:11:19,163
Aim!
Break the bars!

1646
02:11:19,163 --> 02:11:22,375
[SHOUTING]

1647
02:11:33,469 --> 02:11:35,095
[HORSE NEIGHS]

1648
02:11:37,348 --> 02:11:38,932
[SHOUTING]

1649
02:11:41,477 --> 02:11:43,688
[♪♪♪]

1650
02:12:25,772 --> 02:12:27,440
Shadows and dust.

1651
02:12:27,440 --> 02:12:29,692
[YELLING]
[PROXIMO SCREAMING]

1652
02:12:35,155 --> 02:12:37,074
[GRUNTING]

1653
02:12:38,367 --> 02:12:40,119
[GRUNTS]

1654
02:12:59,012 --> 02:13:01,098
[NEIGHS]

1655
02:13:01,098 --> 02:13:03,643
[CRICKETS CHIRPING]

1656
02:13:05,603 --> 02:13:06,729
[BIRDCALL]

1657
02:13:06,729 --> 02:13:07,939
[HORSE NEIGHS]

1658
02:13:07,939 --> 02:13:09,106
[BIRDCALL]

1659
02:13:09,106 --> 02:13:10,190
Maximus!

1660
02:13:14,821 --> 02:13:17,030
[GAGGING]
I'm sorry.

1661
02:13:17,030 --> 02:13:18,449
[GRUNTS]
No!

1662
02:13:43,432 --> 02:13:45,476
It's done.

1663
02:13:52,024 --> 02:13:54,735
And what of my nephew?

1664
02:13:54,735 --> 02:13:57,070
And what of his mother?

1665
02:13:58,906 --> 02:14:01,701
Should they share
her lover's fate?

1666
02:14:03,243 --> 02:14:05,830
Or should
I be merciful?

1667
02:14:07,999 --> 02:14:10,501
Commodus the Merciful.

1668
02:14:16,465 --> 02:14:19,218
Lucius will
stay with me now.

1669
02:14:19,218 --> 02:14:20,928
And if his mother...

1670
02:14:23,055 --> 02:14:26,475
so much as looks at me...

1671
02:14:26,475 --> 02:14:29,520
in a manner
that displeases me...

1672
02:14:30,730 --> 02:14:32,773
he will die.

1673
02:14:35,818 --> 02:14:38,153
If she decides...

1674
02:14:38,153 --> 02:14:40,781
to be noble...

1675
02:14:40,781 --> 02:14:44,368
and takes
her own life...

1676
02:14:44,368 --> 02:14:46,412
he will die.

1677
02:14:49,122 --> 02:14:51,166
And as for you,

1678
02:14:53,920 --> 02:14:56,630
you will love me...

1679
02:14:56,630 --> 02:14:58,841
as I loved you.

1680
02:15:00,009 --> 02:15:02,511
You will provide me
with an heir...

1681
02:15:02,511 --> 02:15:04,805
of pure blood...

1682
02:15:04,805 --> 02:15:07,850
so that Commodus
and his progeny...

1683
02:15:07,850 --> 02:15:10,394
will rule for
a thousand years.

1684
02:15:14,440 --> 02:15:17,026
Am I not merciful?

1685
02:15:38,297 --> 02:15:40,883
[SHOUTING]
Am I not merciful?

1686
02:15:52,770 --> 02:15:56,482
CROWD:
Maximus! Maximus!
Maximus!

1687
02:15:58,109 --> 02:16:00,193
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

1688
02:16:09,453 --> 02:16:12,289
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

1689
02:16:12,289 --> 02:16:14,291
Maximus!
Maximus!

1690
02:16:27,972 --> 02:16:30,016
[CHANTING CONTINUES IN DISTANCE]

1691
02:16:37,523 --> 02:16:39,733
Maximus.

1692
02:16:39,733 --> 02:16:42,069
Maximus.

1693
02:16:42,069 --> 02:16:44,071
Maximus.

1694
02:16:45,280 --> 02:16:47,407
They call for you.

1695
02:16:48,993 --> 02:16:52,913
The general
who became a slave.

1696
02:16:52,913 --> 02:16:56,125
The slave
who became a gladiator.

1697
02:16:57,376 --> 02:17:00,504
The gladiator
who defied an emperor.

1698
02:17:02,089 --> 02:17:03,966
A striking story.

1699
02:17:03,966 --> 02:17:07,803
Now the people want to know
how the story ends.

1700
02:17:10,263 --> 02:17:12,599
Only a famous death
will do.

1701
02:17:13,976 --> 02:17:17,228
And what could be
more glorious...

1702
02:17:17,228 --> 02:17:21,316
than to challenge the Emperor
himself in the great arena?

1703
02:17:23,485 --> 02:17:25,612
You would fight me?

1704
02:17:25,612 --> 02:17:26,989
Why not?

1705
02:17:26,989 --> 02:17:30,743
Do you think I'm afraid?

1706
02:17:30,743 --> 02:17:33,662
I think you have been afraid
all your life.

1707
02:17:33,662 --> 02:17:37,791
Unlike Maximus the Invincible,
who knows no fear?

1708
02:17:39,334 --> 02:17:41,378
[CHUCKLES]

1709
02:17:43,338 --> 02:17:47,634
I knew a man who once said,
"Death smiles at us all.

1710
02:17:47,634 --> 02:17:51,764
All a man can do
is smile back."

1711
02:17:51,764 --> 02:17:53,724
I wonder.

1712
02:17:53,724 --> 02:17:56,143
Did your friend
smile at his own death?

1713
02:17:57,103 --> 02:17:59,146
You must know.

1714
02:18:01,356 --> 02:18:03,067
He was your father.

1715
02:18:07,196 --> 02:18:10,950
You loved my father,
I know.

1716
02:18:10,950 --> 02:18:13,953
But so did I.

1717
02:18:13,953 --> 02:18:16,413
That makes us brothers,
doesn't it?

1718
02:18:18,498 --> 02:18:22,044
Smile for me now,
brother.

1719
02:18:22,044 --> 02:18:24,088
[GROANS]

1720
02:18:25,923 --> 02:18:28,008
Strap on his armor.

1721
02:18:28,008 --> 02:18:29,676
Conceal the wound.

1722
02:18:35,766 --> 02:18:39,145
CROWD:
Maximus! Maximus!
Maximus!

1723
02:18:39,145 --> 02:18:40,980
[CHANTING CONTINUES]

1724
02:18:40,980 --> 02:18:43,190
[♪♪♪]

1725
02:19:23,354 --> 02:19:25,482
SOLDIER:
Ring formation!

1726
02:19:25,482 --> 02:19:28,401
Ring formation!

1727
02:19:28,401 --> 02:19:31,238
[THUNDEROUS CHEERING]

1728
02:19:39,121 --> 02:19:42,457
[WOMAN VOCALIZING]

1729
02:19:57,639 --> 02:20:00,893
MAN:
Off with his head, Maximus!

1730
02:20:08,483 --> 02:20:10,652
[CHEERING]

1731
02:20:10,652 --> 02:20:12,654
[BOTH GRUNTING]

1732
02:21:02,746 --> 02:21:04,664
[GRUNTING]

1733
02:21:04,664 --> 02:21:07,500
Aah!
[CHEERING]

1734
02:21:14,341 --> 02:21:16,093
[PANTING]

1735
02:21:16,093 --> 02:21:17,970
CROWD:
Maximus! Maximus!

1736
02:21:17,970 --> 02:21:19,554
Quintus, sword!

1737
02:21:20,931 --> 02:21:23,809
Give me your sword!

1738
02:21:25,685 --> 02:21:28,521
Sword!
Give me a sword!

1739
02:21:28,521 --> 02:21:29,982
[CROWD BOOING]

1740
02:21:29,982 --> 02:21:31,358
Sheathe your swords!

1741
02:21:31,358 --> 02:21:34,361
QUINTUS:
Sheathe your swords!

1742
02:21:34,361 --> 02:21:36,529
[CROWD CHEERING]

1743
02:21:43,829 --> 02:21:46,039
[♪♪♪]

1744
02:21:50,377 --> 02:21:52,879
[CHEERING]

1745
02:22:07,269 --> 02:22:10,439
[BOTH GRUNTING]

1746
02:22:17,904 --> 02:22:20,199
[CROWD CHEERS]

1747
02:22:23,785 --> 02:22:25,454
[AUDIENCE SILENCES]

1748
02:22:30,376 --> 02:22:32,543
[DAGGER STABS]

1749
02:22:32,543 --> 02:22:35,297
[PANTING]

1750
02:22:35,297 --> 02:22:39,009
[GAGGING]

1751
02:22:39,968 --> 02:22:42,637
[GURGLING]

1752
02:23:25,931 --> 02:23:28,141
[♪♪♪]

1753
02:23:28,850 --> 02:23:31,978
[WOMAN VOCALIZING]

1754
02:23:48,787 --> 02:23:50,789
QUINTUS:
Maximus.

1755
02:23:54,918 --> 02:23:56,462
Maximus.

1756
02:23:56,462 --> 02:23:58,338
Quintus.

1757
02:24:00,173 --> 02:24:01,758
Free my men.

1758
02:24:02,884 --> 02:24:06,805
Senator Gracchus
is to be reinstated.

1759
02:24:06,805 --> 02:24:08,932
There was a dream
that was Rome.

1760
02:24:10,100 --> 02:24:12,894
It shall be realized.

1761
02:24:12,894 --> 02:24:15,564
These are the wishes
of Marcus Aurelius.

1762
02:24:15,564 --> 02:24:18,400
Free the prisoners!
Go!

1763
02:24:24,739 --> 02:24:27,576
[CHILDREN LAUGHING]

1764
02:24:32,122 --> 02:24:34,416
[WOMAN SINGING
IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

1765
02:24:42,215 --> 02:24:44,301
Maximus.

1766
02:24:45,885 --> 02:24:47,638
Lucius is safe.

1767
02:25:03,320 --> 02:25:05,989
[SIGHING]
Go to them.

1768
02:25:13,788 --> 02:25:17,626
[SINGING CONTINUES]

1769
02:25:28,094 --> 02:25:30,514
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

1770
02:25:54,246 --> 02:25:56,665
You're home.

1771
02:26:22,691 --> 02:26:26,111
Is Rome worth
one good man's life?

1772
02:26:29,656 --> 02:26:31,991
We believed it once.

1773
02:26:34,035 --> 02:26:36,079
Make us
believe it again.

1774
02:26:40,375 --> 02:26:42,877
He was a soldier
of Rome.

1775
02:26:46,214 --> 02:26:48,049
Honor him.

1776
02:26:48,049 --> 02:26:51,136
Who will help me
carry him?

1777
02:27:34,845 --> 02:27:36,723
Now we are free.

1778
02:27:42,979 --> 02:27:45,148
I will see you again.

1779
02:27:47,651 --> 02:27:50,320
But not yet.

1780
02:27:50,320 --> 02:27:52,322
Not yet.

1781
02:27:55,492 --> 02:27:58,370
[SINGING CONTINUES]

1782
02:31:09,435 --> 02:31:11,646
[♪♪♪]

